{"title_page": "Reactions to the disappearance of Madeleine McCann", "text_new": "{{See also|Sightings of Madeleine McCann}}\n{{Main|Disappearance of Madeleine McCann}}\n[[File:Madeleine FA Cup Final 2007.jpg|right|300px|thumb|<center>Appeal at the [[FA Cup Final 2007|2007 FA Cup Final]]</center>]]\nOn the evening of Thursday, 3 May 2007, shortly before her fourth birthday, a [[British people|British]] child, Madeleine McCann, went missing from a holiday apartment in [[Praia da Luz]] in the [[Algarve]] in Portugal, in which she was staying with her parents.\n\nThe Portuguese police investigation into her disappearance closed in July 2008. [[Scotland Yard]] in May 2011 began a review of the case , [[Operation Grange]], and in April 2012 announced their belief that Madeleine might still be alive.<ref>{{cite news |title=Madeleine McCann 'could be alive' say detectives as new image released |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=25 April 2012 |accessdate=25 April 2012 |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/madeleinemccann/9225661/Madeleine-McCann-could-be-alive-say-detectives-as-new-image-released.html}}</ref>\n\nIn the weeks following her disappearance, Madeleine's parents implemented a successful [[#By the family|publicity campaign]] that kept her in the public eye. This resulted in a wide-reaching international response, both in the media and by the public, which led to some criticism that the [[#Of the media coverage|media attention]] was excessive. There was also comment that the UK media had unfairly [[#Objectivity of the coverage|criticised the Portuguese police]].\n\n==Publicity==\n\n===By the family===\n\nAn official website for the search was set up, and the McCann family broadcast two early video appeals.<ref>{{Cite web | title = News Items | work=findmadeleine.com | publisher=McCann Family | date = 21 May 2007 | url = http://www.findmadeleine.com/news/ | accessdate = 21 May 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070519053412/http://www.findmadeleine.com/news/ |archivedate = 19 May 2007}}</ref> The first was a photograph and video montage set to [[Simple Minds]]' song \"[[Don't You (Forget About Me)]]\" and included an animation of the word LOOK in [[uppercase]] with a reproduction of her [[coloboma]] as a radial line inside the first letter O, which blinks.<ref>{{Cite video|people=Madeline McCann |title=Picture Video |publisher=McCann Family, [[Sky News]] |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/video/videoplayer/0,,31200-1266128,00.html |date=18 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070618174409/http://news.sky.com/skynews/video/videoplayer/0%2C%2C31200-1266128%2C00.html |archivedate=18 June 2007 }}</ref> The second featured a montage of images with a voice-over by actress [[Zo\u00eb Wanamaker]] mentioning her coloboma, seeking information about her whereabouts, and asking people to download and display a poster of her from the official site.<ref>{{Cite video|people=Madeline McCann, [[Zo\u00eb Wanamaker]] (voice) |title=Video Appeal |publisher=McCann Family, [[Sky News]] |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/video/videoplayer/0,,31200-1266568,00.html |date=21 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609095553/http://news.sky.com/skynews/video/videoplayer/0%2C%2C31200-1266568%2C00.html |archivedate= 9 June 2007 }}</ref>\n \nThe family said that part of the money raised from [[#Madeleine's Fund|Madeleine's Fund]] would go towards hiring professional campaigners, with a view to achieving the same saturation level of publicity across Europe as had been attained in the UK and the [[Algarve]].<ref>{{Cite news | last = Tremlett | first = Giles | title = Multinationals get behind hunt for Madeleine |work=The Guardian | date = 18 May 2007 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/crime/article/0,,2082626,00.html#article_continue | accessdate = 3 June 2007 | location=London}}</ref> The family based themselves in the same holiday resort from the time of the disappearance and stated then that they would not leave until Madeleine was located. Though as the campaign progressed, they ended up visiting   the Vatican City, Spain, Germany, and Morocco for it, and on 5 June, they made an appeal on the British TV programme ''[[Crimewatch]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Ian Herbert|title=Madeleine 'sightings' mount as the agony goes on and on|url=http://news.independent.co.uk/europe/article2562745.ece|work=The Independent|date=20 May 2007|accessdate=21 May 2007|location=London|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070707202709/http://news.independent.co.uk/europe/article2562745.ece|archivedate=7 July 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Edwards | first = Richard | title = No answers as McCanns' campaign marches on |work=The Daily Telegraph | date = 6 June 2007 | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/06/06/nmaddy106.xml | accessdate = 6 June 2007 | location=London}}</ref> However, shortly after being named as [[arguido]]s, the McCanns returned to the UK on 9 September.<ref name=\"journey begun\">{{Cite news | title = Madeleine parents head back to UK |publisher=BBC News | date = 9 September 2007 |accessdate = 9 September 2007 |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6985454.stm}}</ref>\n\nMadeleine's father had already made a brief trip to the UK, on 20 May 2007, to help finalise the campaign for the search for his daughter.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Madeleine's father returns to UK |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk_news/story/0,,2084699,00.html |work=The Guardian |id= |pages= |page= |date=21 May 2007 |accessdate=21 May 2007 |language= |quote= | location=London}}</ref> Gerry McCann visited the United States between 22 and 25 July when he met [[United States Attorney General|US Attorney General]] [[Alberto Gonzales]] and experts from the National and International Centres for Missing and Exploited Children. During interviews on [[Television network|network television]] programmes Gerry was forced to defend leaving the children alone.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Moult | first = Julie | title = Madeleine's father quizzed over decision to leave her on her own |work=[[Daily Mail|Mail on Sunday]] | date = 25 July 2007 | url = http://www.mailonsunday.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/news.html?in_article_id=470179&in_page_id=1770 | accessdate = 26 July 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe family announced on 15 September 2007 that, beginning in a fortnight, they would be spending up to \u00a380,000, from [[#Madeleine's Fund|Madeleine's Fund]], on a new publicity drive, involving newspaper, television, and [[poster]] advertising to further publicise Madeleine's disappearance.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Push for Madeleine ad publicity |publisher=BBC | date = 15 September 2007 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/6996560.stm | accessdate = 16 September 2007 }}</ref> This will include posters in rural parts of Portugal and Spain and television advertisements, in Arabic, in Morocco.<ref>{{Cite news | author=Mark Townsend and James Robinson| title = Arabic advertisements aid Madeleine hunt |work=The Observer | date = 30 September 2007 | url = http://observer.guardian.co.uk/world/story/0,,2180221,00.html | accessdate = 30 September 2007 | location=London}}</ref> In late October the McCanns set up a [[hotline]] + 34 902 300213, operated by [[Private investigator|private detectives]], for people in the [[Iberian Peninsula]] and North Africa to phone with information.<ref>{{Cite news | title = McCanns set up phone line |work=The Scotsman |location=UK | date = 24 October 2007 | url = http://news.scotsman.com/uk.cfm?id=1696492007 | accessdate = 27 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOver Christmas 2007 the family made a television appeal. This had produced, by 27 December 347 phone calls with information with more subsequently.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Hundreds ring hotline after Madeleine plea |work=The Times | date = 27 December 2007 | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article3095509.ece | accessdate = 27 December 2007 | location=London}}</ref> A further video appeal was made, by the parents, at Christmas 2008. This included footage of Madeleine taken in December 2006.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Christmas appeal for Madeleine |publisher=BBC News | date = 21 December 2008 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/7794194.stm | accessdate = 28 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe parents launched a fresh appeal for information, in March 2009, tightly focused on the area where Madeleine went missing. 10,000 leaflets in Portuguese were distributed in Praia da Luz, [[Lagos, Portugal|Lagos]], and [[Burgau, Portugal|Burgau]] together with billboard advertising.<ref>{{Cite news | title = McCann appeal returns to Portugal |publisher=BBC News | date = 24 March 2009 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/7961734.stm | accessdate = 29 March 2009}}</ref> However, many posters were promptly torn down with [[Correio da Manh\u00e3]] reporting that the local people wanted closure.<ref>{{Cite news | title = New Madeleine Posters Torn Down In Anger | publisher=[[Sky News]] | date = 27 March 2009 | author=Laura Bundock | url = http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/UK-News/Madeleine-McCann-New-Posters-Put-Up-In-Portugal-Are-Torn-Down-By-Angry-Algarve-Residents/Article/200903415249908?lpos=UK_News_News_Your_Way_Region_3&lid=NewsYourWay_ARTICLE_15249908_Madeleine_McCann%3A_New_Posters_Put_Up_In_Portugal_Are_Torn_Down_By_Angry_Algarve_Residents | accessdate = 29 March 2009 }}</ref> The McCanns released an image, on 1 May 2009, of the [[Age progression|projected appearance]] of a 6-year-old Madeleine.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Siddique, Haroon|title=Madeleine McCann's parents release picture of how she might look now|work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2009/may/01/madeleine-mccann-picture|date=1 May 2009|accessdate=16 May 2009 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n===By others===\n[[File:Microsoft.co.uk.png|thumb|right|Advertisement on the front page of [[Microsoft]]'s UK website]]\nSeveral unofficial webpages were created following the disappearance, notably on [[social networking]] sites such as Facebook and MySpace, offering support to the McCanns. An unofficial one minute's silence was held for Madeleine on 21 May 2007<ref name=\"silence\"/>, but since it was organised by an anonymous [[viral email]], it was not thought to be widely observed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://uk.news.yahoo.com/skynews/20070521/tuk-silence-held-for-missing-madeleine-m-45dbed5.html|title=Silence Held For Missing Madeleine McCann|publisher=[[Sky News]]|date=21 May 2007|accessdate=21 May 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070523111013/http://uk.news.yahoo.com/skynews/20070521/tuk-silence-held-for-missing-madeleine-m-45dbed5.html |archivedate = 23 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nRobert Murat, a suspect in the investigation, has tried to generate his own publicity by selling his story. However, [[publicist]] [[Max Clifford]] indicated that he would only represent Murat if he was cleared of suspicion of kidnapping.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gulf-times.com/site/topics/article.asp?cu_no=2&item_no=150786&version=1&template_id=38&parent_id=20 |title=Kidnap suspect looks to cash in on ordeal |work=[[Gulf Times]] |date=23 May 2007 |accessdate=23 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930201329/http://www.gulf-times.com/site/topics/article.asp?cu_no=2&item_no=150786&version=1&template_id=38&parent_id=20 |archivedate=30 September 2007 }}</ref> Within the [[Virtual reality|virtual]] world [[Second Life]], a virtual ''Madeleine's Garden'' has been created.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/index.php?storyID=7096 |title=Inside MaddieWorld |publisher=[[The First Post]] |accessdate=31 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070602112523/http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/index.php?storyID=7096 |archivedate= 2 June 2007 }}</ref> In early July, [[Bryan Adams]] dedicated his concert on Malta to Madeleine.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Singer To Dedicate Gig To Madeleine |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=26 June 2007 |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,91210-1272365,00.html |accessdate=26 June 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629025319/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0%2C%2C91210-1272365%2C00.html |archivedate=29 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\n[[J. K. Rowling]] arranged with her publishers for a poster bearing the face of the missing child to be made available to booksellers when ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows]]'' was launched on 21 July. Rowling said that she hoped that the posters would be displayed prominently in shops all over the world.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Rowling in Madeleine poster plea |publisher=BBC News | date = 16 July 2007| accessdate = 17 July 2007 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/6901845.stm}}</ref>\n\n==Political reaction==\nThe Portuguese Ambassador in London, [[Ant\u00f3nio Santana Carlos]] said on 8 May 2007 that the case was of \"great concern\" to Portugal and asked people to trust the police,<ref name=portugalbbc>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/6635463.stm|title=Portugal defends Madeleine police|publisher=BBC News|accessdate = 8 May 2007 | date=8 May 2007}}</ref> amidst growing criticism of their handling of the case.<ref name=\"mirror criticism\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/topstories/tm_headline=clueless%26method=full%26objectid=19067596%26siteid=89520-name_page.html|title=CLUELESS - We reveal errors made by police in kidnap hunt for Maddy|work=Daily Mirror |location=UK|date=9 May 2007|accessdate = 9 May 2007}}</ref> President [[An\u00edbal Cavaco Silva]] announced on 9 May that he was following the case \"with great concern\", adding that the police were \"doing everything to find the child alive.\"<ref name=iafrica>{{Cite news|url=http://iafrica.com/news/worldnews/844830.htm |title=Video tape may show missing Maddie |publisher=[[iAfrica.com]] |date=9 May 2007 |accessdate=8 June 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070613132814/http://iafrica.com/news/worldnews/844830.htm |archivedate=13 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May, [[Tony Blair]]'s spokesperson said that the then [[Prime minister|Prime Minister]] was following the case closely and that \"we are helping in whatever way we can\".<ref name=iafrica /> On 16 May, coinciding with the launch of [[#Madeline's Fund|the fighting fund]], the then [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] [[Gordon Brown]] delivered a similar message to relatives of Madeleine.<ref name=\"Brownhelp\">{{Cite news | title = Brown offers help over Madeleine |publisher=BBC News | date = 16 May 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6661113.stm| accessdate = 26 May 2007 }}</ref> Former [[Deputy Prime Minister]] [[John Prescott]] also commented on the case, saying at [[Prime Minister's Questions|Prime Minister's Question Time]] \"I'm sure that the thoughts of the whole House will be with them at this terrible time.\"<ref name=\"Brownhelp\" />\n\nOn 26 May, a spokesman for the McCann family confirmed that Gordon Brown had telephoned the McCanns.<ref name=\"browntel\">{{Cite news | title = Brown offers support for McCanns |publisher=BBC News | date = 26 May 2007 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6694999.stm | accessdate = 26 May 2007 }}</ref> Although the spokesman stated that the details of the conversations would remain private, he did confirm that \"During them, Mr Brown offered both Gerry and Kate his full support in their efforts to find Madeleine.\"<ref name=\"browntel\" /> In late September [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] [[David Miliband]] telephoned Gerry.<ref name=\"PI search\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article2558233.ece |title= McCanns send sleuths to Morocco |author=Steven Swinford, John Follainin and Mohamed El Hamraoui |work=The Times |date=30 September 2007|accessdate = 30 September 2007 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n[[Federal Minister of Justice (Germany)|The German Justice Minister]], [[Brigitte Zypries]], said at a meeting of [[G8]] justice ministers in Munich on 3 June, that it should be assumed that Madeleine had been abducted by a gang that passes on children to be abused.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Madeleine paedophile gang theory 'is likely' |work=The Scotsman |location=UK | date = 3 June 2007 | url = http://news.scotsman.com/uk.cfm?id=867592007 | accessdate = 4 June 2007 }}</ref> But the Portuguese prime minister, [[Jos\u00e9 S\u00f3crates]], praised investigators in September 2007, following criticism in the British media of the police handling of the case. S\u00f3crates said that he had total confidence in the work carried out by the Portuguese police.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Madeleine prosecutors seek diaries and toys, reports say |work=The Guardian |author=David Batty, James Sturcke |date = 12 September 2007 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/crime/article/0,,2167511,00.html?gusrc=rss&feed=networkfront | accessdate = 12 September 2007 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Theories by experts==\nThe disappearance provoked differing analyses by experts. Shortly after Madeleine went missing two former [[Scotland Yard]] commanders expressed the view that she had been abducted. Roy Ramm considered that it was a carefully planned kidnapping by someone who had been watching the child.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Britons join search for lost toddler |work=The Times |author=John Follain and Jon Ungoed-Thomas |date = 6 May 2007 | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article1752277.ece |accessdate = 13 October 2007 | location=London}}</ref> John O'Connor was of the view that Madeleine had wandered out of the apartment on her own and was subsequently abducted. O'Connor opined that she was likely to be nearby and recommended a thorough search of surrounding occupied premises.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Madeleine's Eye Holds Vital Clue |work=[[Sky News]] |date=14 May 2007 |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,91210-1265416,00.html |accessdate=13 October 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009032301/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0%2C%2C91210-1265416%2C00.html |archivedate= 9 October 2007 }}</ref> This hypothesis was also supported by criminologist [[Mark Williams-Thomas]] who said, in May 2008, that he believed what happened was that Madeleine woke up, walked around the apartment, found the back patio door was insecure and wandered out. It was at this point that she was most likely abducted by an opportunistic predatory paedophile.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Madeleine: 'My Theories On Missing Girl' | publisher=[[Sky News]] | author=Mark Williams-Thomas | date = 1 May 2008 | accessdate = 25 May 2008 |url = http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30000-1314624,00.html| author-link=Mark Williams-Thomas }}</ref>\n\nHowever Paulo Sargento, a [[Criminal psychology|criminal psychologist]] at [[Universidade Lus\u00f3fona|Lus\u00f3fona University]] in [[Lisbon]], had produced in October 2007 a 3D reconstruction of events at the Ocean Club on the evening Madeleine disappeared, and his view was that kidnapping would be inconsistent with the evidence.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Reconstruction 'casts doubt on Madeleine McCann kidnapping' |work=The Times |author=David Brown |date = 9 October 2007 | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/article2622152.ece |accessdate = 12 October 2007 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title = Desaparecimento de Madeleine McCann |work=Videos.sapos |date = 8 October 2007 | url=https://videos.sapo.pt/wvhISANaAzuzEqRpe6Iz |accessdate = 12 October 2007}}</ref> The case was also reviewed by the notable forensic investigator Professor [[David Barclay (academic)|David Barclay]] of [[Robert Gordon University]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.rgu.ac.uk/news/disp_NewsPreview.cfm?PGE_ID=42071&vmenu=2 |title=World renowned forensic investigator and 'Waking the Dead' advisor joins RGU |publisher=[[Robert Gordon University]]|date=3 April 2007|accessdate = 20 October 2007}}</ref> His opinion was that the police were right to consider the McCanns as suspects and that the child is probably dead.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stv.tv/content/news/headlines/display.html?id=opencms:/news/Forensics_expert_defends_Portugese_police_involved_in_Madeleine_case |title=Forensic expert defends Portuguese police involved in Madeleine case |publisher=[[STV (TV network)|STV]] |date=n.d. |accessdate=15 October 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071225204145/http://www.stv.tv/content/news/headlines/display.html?id=opencms%3A%2Fnews%2FForensics_expert_defends_Portugese_police_involved_in_Madeleine_case |archivedate=25 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Comparison and possible relations with the murder of Joana Cipriano==\n{{See also|Murder of Joana Cipriano}}\nJoana Cipriano, a then 8-year-old girl, disappeared on 12 September 2004 from the village of Figueira, only seven miles from [[Praia da Luz]], where Madeleine McCann disappeared on 3 May 2007.<ref name=Watts14Sep2007>{{cite news |last=Watts |first=Alex |date=14 September 2007 |title=Girl's Case 'May Solve McCann Mystery |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,91210-1283987,00.html |url-status=dead |language=English |work=[[Sky News]] |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009185533/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,91210-1283987,00.html |archive-date=9 October 2007 |access-date=14 October 2017 |via=[[Internet Archive]] [[Wayback Machine]]}}</ref> In both cases, the mothers launched campaigns to find their daughters and, in both cases, the local ''Pol\u00edcia Judici\u00e1ria'' investigated the possibility that the mothers had killed their daughters.<ref name=Govan26May2007>{{cite news |last=Govan |first=Fiona |date=28 May 2007 |title=The detectives working as the world watches |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1552718/The-detectives-working-as-the-world-watches.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London |access-date=14 October 2017}}\n*{{cite book |last=Collins |first=Danny |date=2008 |title=Vanished: The Truth about the Disappearance of Madeleine McCann |url=https://books.google.com/?id=iHhVLQAACAAJ |location= |publisher=[[John Blake (journalist)#John Blake Publishing|John Blake Publishing]] |page= |isbn=978-1844546145 |author-link= }} (Note: paperback edition).</ref>\n\nA child protection specialist, Mark Williams-Thomas, who believes that Joana's and Madeleine's disappearances are related, said that the disappearance of two children unknown to each other, within a period of four years in a seven-mile radius, would be a huge coincidence, especially considering that Portugal is a small country with few abductions.<ref name=Watts14Sep2007/> Before Joana's disappearance, the previous first-degree murder of a child in the [[Algarve]] region was in November 1990 and involved a British girl, nine-year-old Rachel Charles, who was abducted and murdered in [[Albufeira]]. Her body was found three days later; a British mechanic, Michael Cook, a friend of the family, was arrested and convicted.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tweedie |first1=Neil |last2=Edwards |first2=Richard |date=12 May 2007 |title=Have police failed Madeleine? |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1551346/Have-police-failed-Madeleine.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London |access-date=14 October 2017 }}\n*On 19 June 1996 a six-year-old German child, Ren\u00e8 Has\u00e8e, also disappeared, from the Amoreira beach near [[Aljezur]] while walking a few metres ahead of his parents; see [http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/2075dmprt.html The Doe Network: Case File 2075DMPRT] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080508221139/http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/2075dmprt.html |date=8 May 2008 }} and [http://en.sevenload.com/photos/Qxy8SOM-Rene-Hasee-vermisst-seit-dem-19-Juni-1996 \"Rene Hasee vermisst seit dem 19.Juni 1996\"]{{dead link|date=June 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}.</ref> Leandro Silva, the [[Common-law marriage|common-law husband]] of Leonor Cipriano, said in 2007 that \"the only difference between the McCanns and us is that we don't have money.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Antezana |first=Fabiola |date=26 September 2007 |title=Detective in McCann Case Investigated For Beating Convicted Child Murderer |url=http://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/story?id=3646987&page=1#.UZeqSoIilDQ |work=[[ABC News]] |location=New York City |access-date=14 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nSeveral similarities between the cases\u2014both girls vanished without trace within {{convert|7|mi}} and less than three years of each other, in both cases officers failed to secure the crime scene, both mothers mounted campaigns to find their daughters and both women were accused of involvement\u2014prompted Joana's family to appeal in 2008 for police to investigate whether there was a link between the disappearances.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Watts |first1=Alex |date=12 May 2008 |title='Disturbing Similarities' With Madeleine |url=http://news.sky.com/story/603144/disturbing-similarities-with-madeleine |url-status=dead |language=English |work=[[Sky News]] |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234140/http://news.sky.com/story/603144/disturbing-similarities-with-madeleine |archive-date=3 March 2016 |access-date=October 14, 2017 |via=[[Internet Archive]] [[Wayback Machine]]}}</ref>\n\n==Fundraising==\n\n===Madeleine's Fund===\nA fundraising company, known as ''Madeleine's Fund: Leaving No Stone Unturned'', was launched in [[Leicester]] on 16 May 2007. The Fund is a limited company, not a [[Charitable organization|registered charity]], because its objectives are not wide enough to satisfy [[Charity Commission]] criteria for UK charities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/09/11/wmaddy1011.xml|title=McCanns may use Madeleine fund for defence\n|work=Daily Telegraph |date=12 September 2007|accessdate = 12 September 2007 | location=London | first=Nick | last=Britten}}</ref> The objectives include helping the extended family with their expenses (to prevent abuse, payments can only be authorised by the independent members of the board who are not family members) and continuing the investigation independently should that prove necessary. Any excess funds would be used to help search for other abducted children.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6662723.stm|title=Madeleine fighting fund launched|publisher=BBC News|date=16 May 2007|accessdate = 16 May 2007}}</ref> The Fund's website reportedly received 58&nbsp;million [[Hit (web request)|hits]] and 16,000 messages of support by 18 May, only two days after its launch.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6668479.stm|title=Madeleine film plan for Cup Final|date=18 May 2007|publisher=BBC News|accessdate = 18 May 2007}}</ref> Over \u00a31,095,000 had been raised by 30 October 2007.<ref>[http://www.bringmadeleinehome.com/news/fund.asp ''Madeleine's Fund: Leaving No Stone Unturned''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070606145016/http://www.bringmadeleinehome.com/news/fund.asp |date=6 June 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"mortgage payments\"/> Two \u00a32,000 monthly re-payments on the McCanns' [[Mortgage loan|mortgage]] were made from the Fund in July and August.<ref name=\"mortgage payments\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/10/30/wmaddy230.xml |title=McCanns used \u00a31m fund to pay mortgage |author=Caroline Gammell\n|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK|date=31 October 2007|accessdate = 20 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Legal costs funding===\nThe trustees of ''Madeleine's Fund'' announced in September that the fund would not be used to pay the McCanns' legal costs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article2441844.ece |title=Parents will have to pay defence costs without Madeleine's Fund |author=Adam Fresco, Patrick Foster and Fran Yeoman |work=The Times |location=UK|date=13 September 2007|accessdate = 13 September 2007 }}</ref> Initially, the McCanns considered setting up a separate appeal fund for legal expenses.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Adam Fresco and David Brown |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article2439634.ece| title=Madeleine's parents consider new fund for legal battle |work=The Times |location=UK|date=12 September 2007|accessdate = 12 September 2007 }}</ref> However, [[Richard Branson]] created a fund for the McCann's legal expenses, including those of their current advisor, [[Michael Caplan]] [[Queen's Counsel|QC]], a solicitor and partner in the London firm of Kingsley Napley.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6997429.stm|title=Branson fund for McCanns' lawyers |publisher=BBC News|date=16 September 2007|accessdate = 16 September 2007}}</ref> [[Stephen Winyard]] came out in December as having contributed \u00a3100,000 to the McCanns' defence fund, which paid for [[Genetic fingerprinting|DNA tests]] carried out on the [[Renault Sc\u00e9nic]] hire car used by the McCanns.<ref name=\"Stephen Winyard\"/> He also revealed [[Brian Kennedy (businessman)|Brian Kennedy]] as another donor.<ref name=\"Stephen Winyard\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.scotsman.com/scotland.cfm?id=1914972007 |title=Scots tycoon attacks 'scurrilous allegations' as he comes out as McCanns' secret funder |author=Michael Howie |work=The Scotsman |location=UK|date=8 December 2007|accessdate = 9 December 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Potential frauds==\nMany unofficial websites were registered which had domain names that contained slight misspellings of Madeleine's name (a practice known as [[typosquatting]]), plus keywords likely to be used in searches. These websites contained material unrelated to Madeleine.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Mills | first = James |author2=Greenhill, Sam  |author3=Rees, Gwyneth | title = Sick web hijackers cash in on Madeleine |work=Daily Mail |location=UK | date = 19 May 2007 | url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/news.html?in_article_id=455885&in_page_id=1770 | accessdate = 22 May 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThere have also been people collecting money on the [[false premise]] that they were representing [[Response to the disappearance of Madeleine McCann#Madeleine's Fund|Madeleine's Fund]], one of whom, Debbie Clifton, was jailed for 90 days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/staffordshire/6284516.stm|title=AMadeleine cash theft woman jailed |publisher=BBC News|date=9 July 2007|accessdate=10 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 June 2007 police arrested an Italian man and a Portuguese woman at a villa in [[Sotogrande]], [[C\u00e1diz]] over allegations that they had tried to defraud the McCanns by claiming a reward for information about their daughter. However, police said that there was no direct link with Madeleine's kidnap.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6251266.stm|title=Italian arrest in Madeleine case|publisher=BBC News|date=28 June 2007|accessdate=28 June 2007}}</ref> Then on 6 July police in the Netherlands arrested a man who allegedly demanded two million euros from the McCanns for information about their missing daughter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article2036933.ece|title=Man held over Madeleine McCann extortion|work=The Times |date=6 July 2007|accessdate=10 July 2007 | location=London | first=David | last=Brown}}</ref>\n\nBritish barrister [[Michael Shrimpton]] presented himself as the \"unofficial representative\" for parents Kate and Gerry McCann, and claimed responsibility for setting up a meeting between them and [[Pope Benedict XVI]].<ref name=\"cnubarrister\" /><ref name=\"cnubomb\" />  According to Shrimpton, Madeleine was being held in or near [[Morocco]] after being smuggled there on a drug-running vessel.<ref name=\"cnubarrister\" /><ref name=\"nazi\" />  Authorities rejected these claims as false and issued a strict warning to Shrimpton not to interfere with the case.<ref name=\"nazi\" /><ref name=\"cnubarrister\" />  Shrimpton was later charged, convicted, and imprisoned for an unrelated hoax.<ref name=\"nazi\" />\n\n==Libel actions==\nThe McCanns announced on 31 August that they were [[Lawsuit|suing]] the Portuguese [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] ''[[Tal & Qual]]'' for [[Slander and libel|libel]]. The newspaper reported that the \"police believe\" that the McCanns killed Madeleine, suggesting she may have died in an accident or from a drugs overdose.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = McCanns to sue Portuguese paper\n |publisher=BBC News\n | date = 31 August 2007\n | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6971662.stm\n | accessdate = 31 August 2007}}</ref> The McCanns' lawyer, Carlos Pinto de Abreu, said the couple's image had been \"dragged through the dirt\" by \"character-assassinating, tabloid-style\" news reports, adding that the press \"has engaged in a horrific exercise in scandal-mongering, replete with rumours and lurid commentaries...to sell more TV time and newspaper space to advertisers\". The police stressed that the McCanns were not suspects.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = McCanns in legal move on newspaper\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 31 August 2007\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uklatest/story/0,,-6888704,00.html\n | accessdate = 31 August 2007\n}} {{Dead link|date=August 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref>\n\n''Tal & Qual'' stood by the story. The journalist who wrote the article, Catarina Vaz Guerreiro, said \"I can't reveal my source, but I have complete trust in them. I strongly believe that the person that gave us this information is telling the truth.\"<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = Top detective in Madeleine inquiry backs 'innocent' McCanns\n |work=Daily Mail |location=UK\n | date = 31 August 2007\n | url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/news.html?in_article_id=478885&in_page_id=1770\n | accessdate = 31 August 2007\n| first=Sam\n| last=Greenhill}}</ref> The paper ceased publication after 28 September 2007, because of a drop in circulation.<ref name=\"publico\">{{Cite news\n |title=Jornal \"Tal & Qual\" acaba amanh\u00e3 \n |publisher=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]] \n |date=27 September 2007 \n |url=http://ultimahora.publico.clix.pt/noticia.aspx?id=1305931&idCanal=undefined \n |accessdate=28 September 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215052223/http://ultimahora.publico.clix.pt/noticia.aspx?id=1305931 \n |archivedate=15 February 2008 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n\nThe ASFIC's (Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Sindical dos Funcion\u00e1rios de Investiga\u00e7\u00e3o Criminal da Pol\u00edcia Judici\u00e1ria) General Secretary, Carlos Garcia, declared on 10 August 2007 that the [[Trade union|union]] representing the PJ intended to take legal action against those British journalists who had accused Portuguese police officers of forging evidence. He stated that, at the beginning of the investigation, a joint working group had been created with the British police, and that they had been working in close cooperation. Thus when the Portuguese police is criticised, so too is the British police. He claimed that the number of abductions resulting in murder was a decisive factor that determined the different methods of investigation adopted by the two forces.<ref>{{Cite news\n |title      = Agentes da PJ querem processar jornalistas ingleses\n |work       = [[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]\n |date       = 18 August 2007\n |url        = http://ultimahora.publico.clix.pt/noticia.aspx?id=1301854\n |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130416152959/http://ultimahora.publico.clix.pt/noticia.aspx?id=1301854\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 16 April 2013\n |accessdate = 1 November 2007\n}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2008, the McCanns launched a [[libel]] suit against the ''[[Daily Express]]'' and its sister newspaper, the ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]'', as well as their Sunday equivalents, following the newspapers' coverage of the case. The action concerned more than 100 stories across the four newspapers, which accused the McCanns of causing Madeleine's death and then covering it up.<ref name=\"Damages due\"/> One immediate consequence of the action was that Express Newspapers pulled all references to Madeleine from its websites.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = Express titles cut back McCann coverage\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | author=Leigh Holmwood\n | date = 13 March 2008\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/mar/13/pressandpublishing.dailyexpress\n | accessdate = 17 March 2008\n}}</ref> In a settlement reached at the [[High Court of Justice]], the newspapers agreed to run a front-page apology to the McCanns on 19 March 2008, publish another apology on the front pages of the Sunday editions of 23 March and make a statement of apology at the High Court.<ref name=\"Damages due\">{{Cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7303801.stm | title=Damages due over McCann stories | publisher=BBC News Online | date=18 March 2008 | accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref>  ''Guardian'' media commentator [[Roy Greenslade]] said it was \"unprecedented\" for four major newspapers to offer front-page apologies, but also said that it was more than warranted given that the papers had committed \"a substantial libel\" that shamed the entire British press.<ref>[[Roy Greenslade|Greenslade, Roy]]. [https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2008/mar/19/expressandstarapologiesto Express and Star apologies to McCanns bring all journalism into disrepute]. [[The Guardian]], 19 March 2008.</ref>\n\nIn its apology, the ''Express'' stated that \"a number of articles in the newspaper have suggested that the couple caused the death of their missing daughter Madeleine and then covered it up. We acknowledge that there is no evidence whatsoever to support this theory and that Kate and Gerry are completely innocent of any involvement in their daughter's disappearance.\"<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://www.dailyexpress.co.uk/posts/view/38490 | title=Kate and Gerry McCann: Sorry |work=Daily Express |location=UK | date=19 March 2008 | accessdate = 19 March 2008}}</ref> The McCanns also accepted \u00a3550,000 ($1.1&nbsp;million) damages and costs.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/europe/03/19/mccann.newspapers/index.html | title=McCanns win $1M libel damages | publisher=CNN | date=19 March 2008 |accessdate = 19 March 2008}}</ref> They promised to pay the damages into ''Madeleine's Fund''.<ref name=\"Damages due\"/>\n\nRobert Murat instigated defamation proceedings against [[Sky News]] and 11 British newspapers, in April 2008. He used London solicitors Simons Muirhead & Burton on a [[Contingent fee|conditional fee]] agreement. The first paper to settle was ''[[The Scotsman]]'' who published an apology on 15 May but paid no damages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=41189&c=1 |title=Scotsman apologises to Robert Murat for defamatory Madeline McCann story |date=16 May 2008 |accessdate=18 May 2008 |author=Patrick Smith |publisher=[[Press Gazette]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080520233811/http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=41189&c=1 |archivedate=20 May 2008 }}</ref> The newspaper groups [[Associated Newspapers Ltd|Associated Newspapers]], [[Express Newspapers]], [[Trinity Mirror|MGN Limited]] and [[News International|News Group Newspapers]] settled with Murat, on 17 July, for a \u00a3600,000 payout. They also issued a public apology in the [[High Court of Justice|High Court]].<ref name=\"Robert Murat accepts \u00a3600,000\"/> [[BSkyB]] also paid him damages in a separate libel case.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/madeleinemccann/3458813/Madeleine-McCann-Robert-Murat-accepts-libel-damages-from-BSkyB.html |title=Madeleine McCann: Robert Murat accepts libel damages from BSkyB |publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London |date=14 November 2008 |accessdate=19 September 2011}}</ref> Sergey Malinka, and Murat's girlfriend, Michaela Walczuch, accepted more than \u00a3100,000 each.<ref name=\"Robert Murat accepts \u00a3600,000\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article4350087.ece |title=Robert Murat accepts \u00a3600,000 after Madeleine McCann allegations |date=17 July 2008 |accessdate=17 July 2008 |author=Nico Hines |work=The Times | location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe friends of the McCanns, known as the [[Disappearance of Madeleine McCann#Friends|Tapas Seven]], were awarded around \u00a3375,000 in damages and secured printed apologies from Express Newspapers. The friends have donated the settlement monies to the Fund. The apologies, printed in both the Daily Express and Daily Star, said \"In articles ... we suggested that the holiday companions of Kate and Gerry McCann might have covered up the true facts concerning Madeleine McCann's disappearance and/or misled the authorities investigating her disappearance. We also reported speculation that ... Dr Russell O'Brien, was suspected of involvement with Madeleine's abduction. We now accept that these suggestions should never have been made and were completely untrue. ...\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/mediatechnologyandtelecoms/media/3206334/Madeleine-McCann-Daily-Express-publishes-apology-to-Tapas-Seven.html |title=Madeleine McCann: Daily Express publishes apology to 'Tapas Seven' |date=16 October 2008 |accessdate=17 October 2008 |author=Matthew Moore  |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK }}</ref>\n\nThe McCanns applied for an injunction, on 8 December 2009, prohibiting the sale of the book, written by Gon\u00e7alo Amaral, ''Maddie, a Verdade da Mentira'' (''Maddie, the Truth of the Lie''), and launched a libel suit against Amaral.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.correiomanha.pt/noticia.aspx?contentid=9F1855F4-CDF8-493C-8478-EF3D122CEFE1&channelid=00000010-0000-0000-0000-000000000010&h=3 |title=McCann no julgamento do livro de Gon\u00e7alo Amaral |date=8 December 2009 |accessdate=8 December 2009 |publisher=[[Correio da Manh\u00e3]]}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* ''Maddie 129'', {{ISBN|978-989-8028-61-7}}, that covers the 129 days between Madeleine's disappearance and the McCanns' return to Rothley. The book claims to identify contradictions and unanswered questions in the accounts of the McCanns and their friends. It was published in early November 2007, in English by [[Prime Books]], and written by two Portuguese journalists Hern\u00e2ni Carvalho and Lu\u00eds Maia.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = Madeleine book notes the 'contradictions'\n | author=Ned Temko\n |work=The Observer |location=UK\n | date = 4 November 2007\n | url = http://books.guardian.co.uk/news/articles/0,,2205019,00.html\n | accessdate = 13 November 2007 }}</ref>\n* ''A Culpa dos McCann'' (The Guilt of the McCanns), {{ISBN|989-8014-81-4}}, was published in Portugal in December 2007. Written by Portuguese daily newspaper [[Correio da Manh\u00e3]] editor-in-chief Manuel Catarino, it was published by [[Guerra & Paz]].<ref>{{Cite news\n |title=Madeleine book notes the 'contradictions' \n |author=Alison Flood \n |work=[[Bookseller.com]] \n |date=3 December 2007 \n |url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/49158-second-mccann-book-in-portugal.html \n |accessdate=9 December 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071206224157/http://www.thebookseller.com/news/49158-second-mccann-book-in-portugal.html \n |archivedate= 6 December 2007 \n}}</ref>\n* ''Madeleine: A Heartbreaking and Extraordinary Disappearance'', {{ISBN|978-0-85079-348-2}}, was published in December 2007 by [[Daily Express|Express Newspapers]] and written by Robert Downing.\n* ''A Estrela de Madeleine'' (The Star of Madeleine), {{ISBN|978-972-23-3890-5}}, written by Paulo Pereira Crist\u00f3v\u00e3o, was published by Editorial Presen\u00e7a.<ref>{{Cite news\n |title      = Das p\u00e1ginas dos jornais para o neg\u00f3cio dos livros\n |author     = Patr\u00edcia Jesus\n |work       = [[Di\u00e1rio de Not\u00edcias]]\n |date       = 21 July 2008\n |url        = https://dn.sapo.pt/especiais/Interior.aspx?content_id=981318&especial=Caso%20Maddie&seccao=SOCIEDADE//index.html\n |accessdate = 7 June 2009\n}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* ''O Enigma da Praia da Luz'' (The Enigma of Praia da Luz), {{ISBN|978-989-8014-91-7}}, was written by Francisco Duarte de Carvalho and was published by Editora Guerra & Paz.\n* ''Maddie, a Verdade da Mentira'' (Maddie, the Truth of the Lie), {{ISBN|978-989-8174-12-3}}, written by Gon\u00e7alo Amaral, who had originally headed the police investigation, was published by Guerra & Paz on 24 July 2008. In the book, Amaral detailed his belief that Madeleine died in the family's holiday apartment.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = Detective's book claims Madeleine McCann died in apartment\n | author=Haroon Siddique\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 24 July 2008\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/jul/24/madeleinemccann.portugal\n | accessdate = 26 July 2008}}</ref>\n*''What really happened to Madeleine McCann?'' subtitled '60 reasons which suggest that she was not abducted', {{ISBN|978-0-9507954-7-8}}, was written by Tony Bennett and was published on 31 October 2008 by The Madeleine Foundation.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = Madeleine\n | date = 31 October 2008\n | id ={{ASIN|095079547X|country=it}}\n }}</ref>\n*''Madeleine'', {{ISBN|978-0-593-06791-8}}, was written by Kate McCann and was published by [[Bantam Press]] on 12 May 2011.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = What Really Happened to Madeleine McCann?: 60 Reasons Which Suggest She Was Not Abducted\n | date = 12 May 2011\n | id ={{ASIN|0593067916|country=uk}}\n }}</ref>\n\n==Film and television==\n\n===BBC Panorama===\nThe BBC ''[[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]]'' current affairs programme screened an edition called 'The Mystery of Madeleine McCann' on 19 November 2007. It attracted 5.3&nbsp;million viewers.<ref name=\"ITV documentary\">{{Cite news\n | title = McCanns mull ITV documentary offer\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | author=Leigh Holmwood\n | date = 11 March 2008\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/mar/11/madeleinemccann.itv\n | accessdate = 11 March 2008 }}</ref>\nThe programme reviewed the evidence that was currently publicly available but did not come to a conclusion on what happened to Madeleine.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = The Mystery of Madeleine McCann\n |publisher=BBC\n | date = 18 November 2007\n | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/panorama/7100536.stm\n | accessdate = 30 November 2007}}</ref>\nThe original producer of the programme walked out, claiming that criticism of the media and the Portuguese police had been toned down for the broadcast version.<ref name=\"ITV documentary\"/>\n\n===Proposed documentaries===\nThe McCanns have given permission for talks to open about the possibility of the disappearance being made into a documentary film. Spokesman [[Clarence Mitchell (journalist)|Clarence Mitchell]] confirmed that a meeting, with [[Talent agent|talent agency]] and production company [[IMG (business)|IMG]] to discuss a possible film, was held in December 2007, but the proposal was abandoned.<ref name=\"ITV documentary\"/><ref>{{Cite news\n | title = Parents may turn Madeleine McCann story into a Hollywood movie\n | author=Rajeev Syal and Dominic Kennedy\n |work=The Times |location=UK\n | date = 9 January 2008\n | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/panorama/7100536.stm\n | accessdate = 9 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nMitchell also confirmed, in March 2008, that discussions were taking place with [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] and other companies over the possibility of the McCanns appearing in a documentary, which would focus on missing children in general and the different initiatives used to help look for them.<ref name=\"ITV documentary\"/> The programme, ''Madeleine, One Year On: Campaign For Change'', was broadcast on [[ITV1]] on 30 April 2008. The programme's producers said the McCanns had no editorial control and were not paid, although \u00a310,000 was donated to the Find Madeleine Fund.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Rachel Williams|title=Madeleine anniversary: McCanns tell of regrets in TV documentary|work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/apr/30/madeleinemccann.itv|date=30 April 2008|accessdate=30 April 2008 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n===TVI documentary===\nA television documentary, ''Maddie, a Verdade da Mentira'' (''Maddie, the Truth of the Lie''), based on the book, by Gon\u00e7alo Amaral, of the same name, was produced by [[Televis\u00e3o Independente|TVI]]. It was broadcast on 13 April 2009.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.novelasnacionais.com/tvi/noticias/1761-maddie%E2%80%93a-verdade-da-mentira-na-tvi |title=\"Maddie \u2013 A Verdade da Mentira\" na TVI |date=10 April 2009 |accessdate=8 December 2009 |publisher=[[Novelas Nacionais]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714203046/http://www.novelasnacionais.com/tvi/noticias/1761-maddie%E2%80%93a-verdade-da-mentira-na-tvi |archivedate=14 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The documentary pulled in an audience of over 2&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://dn.sapo.pt/especiais/interior.aspx?content_id=1225510&especial=Caso%20Maddie&seccao=SOCIEDADE |title='A Verdade da Mentira' pela Europa |date=8 May 2009 |accessdate=8 December 2009 |publisher=[[Correio da Manh\u00e3]] }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Implications for television programmes and films==\nOn 9 May 2007, [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] announced it would be rewriting a planned child kidnap [[Plot (narrative)|plot]], despite having already filmed some scenes, from their popular soap ''[[Coronation Street]]''.<ref name=\"corrie\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6638171.stm|title=Street rethinks child kidnap plot|publisher=BBC News|date=9 May 2007|accessdate=25 May 2007}}</ref> Similarly, on 23 May, the [[BBC TV|BBC]] also announced that it was scrapping a [[Subplot|storyline]] from rival soap ''[[EastEnders]]'', that had already been filmed, which also was to feature the kidnapping of a child.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/6682939.stm|title=EastEnders kidnap plot scrapped|work=[[BBC News]]|date=23 May 2007|accessdate=14 May 2009}}</ref> In both cases these plot lines were removed or altered due to the parallel with the Madeleine case, and because the channels did not want to cause further distress to the McCann family.<ref name=\"corrie\" />\n\n[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] was criticised, in September 2007,  over the showing of ''[[Torn (TV series)|Torn]]'', a three-part original drama series. The plot involved the disappearance of a four-year-old girl and the family's search for her. ITV responded to the criticism by stating that ''Torn'' had been written two years earlier and filmed two months before Madeleine disappeared.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Farmer|first=Ben|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1563414/ITV-criticised-over-Madeleine-McCann-drama.html|title=ITV criticised over 'Madeleine McCann' drama |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=18 September 2007|accessdate=3 August 2009 | location=London}}</ref> Also in September 2007, actor and director [[Ben Affleck]] postponed the UK release of his film ''[[Gone Baby Gone]]'', which had been scheduled for release on 28 December,\nto 18 April 2008. Its plot centres on the abduction of a four-year-old girl who is left at home alone by her mother. The actress who plays the girl, [[Madeline O'Brien]], reportedly resembles Madeleine. According to Affleck, the release of the film in Britain was delayed because those involved with the film didn't want to \"touch a nerve or inflame anybody's sensitivities.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Franklin|first=Katie|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6992601.stm|title=US film pulled over McCann case |author2=Neil Smith |publisher=BBC News|date=13 September 2007|accessdate=13 September 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Tributes==\n[[File:Tributes for Madeleine McCann, Rothley, 17 May 2007.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Tributes in [[Rothley]] on 17 May 2007]]\nChurch services were held in Portugal and the UK on 3 May 2008, to mark the first anniversary of Madeleine's disappearance.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Esther Addley|title=Services to mark year since Madeleine vanished|work=The Guardian |location=UK|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/may/03/madeleinemccann.internationalcrime|date=3 May 2008|accessdate=3 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Appeals==\nThere were many appeals for Madeleine's safe return, including from her family, celebrities, church leaders, and the police.\n\n===From the family===\nHer father, Gerry McCann, said, \"Words cannot describe the anguish and despair that we are feeling. Please, if you have Madeleine, let her come home to her Mummy, Daddy, brother and sister.\"<ref name=\"yahoo story\">{{Cite news|url=http://uk.news.yahoo.com/rtrs/20070505/tpl-uk-portugal-girl-4b8df73.html|title=Abducted girl's parents pray for her safe return|publisher=[[Reuters]]|author=Axel Bugge|date=6 May 2007|accessdate = 6 May 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070508145030/http://uk.news.yahoo.com/rtrs/20070505/tpl-uk-portugal-girl-4b8df73.html |archivedate = 8 May 2007}}</ref> He went on to say that the family would leave \"no stone unturned\" in the search for Madeleine and that he and his wife \"remained positive.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6645341.stm|title=Madeleine parents 'won't give up'|publisher=BBC News|date=11 May 2007|accessdate = 11 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nMadeleine's aunt, Philomena McCann, drew up a poster<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www1.sky.com/news/Madeleine.pdf |title=Copy of 'Missing Madeleine' poster |publisher=[[Sky News]] |accessdate=9 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612042338/http://www1.sky.com/news/Madeleine.pdf |archivedate=12 June 2007 }}</ref> to circulate in a chain email to help find the child. She also commented during a live phone interview that there was little coverage of the case in other countries apart from the UK and Portugal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,91210-1264740,00.html |title=Madeleine's Family Send Out Email Poster |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=9 May 2007 |accessdate=9 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070512095111/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0%2C%2C91210-1264740%2C00.html |archivedate=12 May 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===From the police===\nOn 21 May 2007, the British [[Child Exploitation and Online Protection Centre]] (CEOP) reported that British police are calling on visitors to the Ocean Club Resort, Praia da Luz, or the surrounding areas in the two weeks leading up to Madeleine's disappearance on Thursday 3 May to provide copies of any relevant photographs taken during their stay, in an attempt to identify an abductor using a [[Biometrics|biometric]] [[Facial recognition system|facial recognition application]], through which the features of bystanders in those photographs could be compared to those of international sex offenders and other criminals.<ref name=photographs>{{Cite news|url=http://www.madeleine.ceopupload.com/|title=Help find Madeleine McCann|publisher=[[Child Exploitation and Online Protection Centre]]|date=21 May 2007|accessdate=21 May 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070523075031/http://madeleine.ceopupload.com/|archivedate=23 May 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-1266780,00.html |title=Madeleine's Dad Arrives Back In Portugal |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=22 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070615052316/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0%2C%2C30100-1266780%2C00.html |archivedate=15 June 2007 }}</ref> By 1 June, over one thousand photographs had been uploaded.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/932ba02b5ba8922f8de6dfd1e0f97529.html |title=Madeleine McCann: Photos flood in |publisher=[[ITV News]] |date=1 June 2007 |accessdate=2 June 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929090400/http://www.itv.com/news/932ba02b5ba8922f8de6dfd1e0f97529.html |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===From religious leaders===\nOn 11 May 2007 Roman Catholic [[Archbishop]] [[Mario Joseph Conti|Mario Conti]] of [[Glasgow]] said that his prayers would continue for the safe return of Madeleine<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.christiantoday.com/article/1m.reward.offered.for.missing.madeleine/10740.htm|title=\u00a31m Reward Offered for Missing Madeleine|publisher=[[Christian Today]]|date=11 May 2007|accessdate = 2 June 2007}}</ref> Then on 30 May, [[Pope Benedict XVI]], at an audience in the [[Apostolic Palace|Vatican]] with the McCanns, promised to pray for the girl's safe return.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/pope/story/0,,2091210,00.html|title=Madeleine's parents meet Pope|work=The Guardian |location=UK|date=30 May 2007|accessdate = 30 May 2007|first=Peter | last=Walker}}</ref>\n\n===From sport===\n\n====From football====\n[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] footballer [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], who is Portuguese, made a televised appeal on [[Manchester United TV|MUTV]] for her safe return saying \"I was very upset to hear of the abduction of Madeleine McCann and I appeal to anyone with information to come forward - please come forward.\"<ref name=portugalbbc /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/breaking/story.asp?j=14248132&p=y4z48y78&n=14248220&x=|title=Star Ronaldo in Madeleine appeal|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|date=8 May 2007|accessdate = 9 May 2007}}</ref> [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and [[England national football team|England]] footballer [[John Terry]] and his Portuguese teammate [[Paulo Ferreira]] said that they were \"devastated to hear that young Maddy was abducted. Our thoughts and feelings go out to her parents, her family and we are urging anyone out there with any information at all, please, please, please come forward.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/index_0456c056818c3d70b8184f9f88a1701e.html |title=Paedophile link probed in Madeleine hunt |publisher=[[ITV News]] |date=9 May 2007 |accessdate=9 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929121942/http://www.itv.com/news/index_0456c056818c3d70b8184f9f88a1701e.html |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref> On 11 May 2007, [[David Beckham]] also made a public appeal. \"If you have seen this little girl please could you go to your local authorities or police and give any information that you have,\" said Beckham, holding up a poster with a photograph of Madeleine.<ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/05/11/europe/EU-GEN-Spain-Beckham-Appeal.php \"David Beckham appeals for information on missing toddler Madeleine McCann\"], ''[[International Herald Tribune]]'', 11 May 2007</ref>\n\nAfter a picture was released of Madeleine in an [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] shirt, Everton's Portuguese footballers [[Nuno Valente]] and [[Manuel Henriques Tavares Fernandes|Manuel Fernandes]] appealed for any news on her whereabouts and [[Phil Neville]] issued the following statement on behalf of the club. \"Everton has fans all over the world and I know that they, along with everyone connected with the football club, are hoping and praying for Madeleine's safe return. Our thoughts are very much with the family at this extremely distressing time.\" Manager [[David Moyes]] added \"Everybody here is desperately wanting to hear good news and my thoughts and prayers are with the family. If anybody out there knows anything, please come forward\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/statement-for-madeleine.html|title=Everton appeal for Madeleine|publisher=[[Everton F.C.]]|date=11 May 2007|accessdate=11 May 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070512083826/http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/statement-for-madeleine.html|archive-date=12 May 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] footballer [[Neil Lennon]] made an appeal for Madeleine's safety, and yellow armbands were worn on 12 May 2007 against [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] to mark her fourth birthday.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/stories/news_110507090633.aspx |title=Celtic players to wear yellow armbands |publisher=[[Celtic F.C.]] |date=11 May 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513024027/http://www.celticfc.net/news/stories/news_110507090633.aspx |archivedate=13 May 2007 }}</ref>\n\nA video appealing for help with the search for Madeleine was broadcast to Spanish football fans visiting the city of [[Glasgow]] for the [[2007 UEFA Cup Final]] on 16 May.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/6664081.stm|title=Spanish fans shown Madeleine film|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|date=16 May 2007|accessdate = 19 May 2007}}</ref> Another film was aired at half-time during the English [[FA Cup]] Final on 19 May.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,91210-1266418,00.html |title=Candle-Lit Vigil And Prayers For Madeleine |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=18 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070604081748/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0%2C%2C91210-1266418%2C00.html |archivedate= 4 June 2007 }}</ref> Before their departure for the [[2007 UEFA Champions League Final]] on Monday 21 May, [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]'s squad were photographed with a banner appealing for any information on Madeleine's whereabouts.<ref name=\"silence\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6677037.stm|title=Minute silence held for Madeleine|publisher=BBC News|date=21 May 2007|accessdate=21 May 2007}}</ref>\n\n====From cricket====\nThe [[England cricket team]] wore yellow ribbons during the [[Lord's Cricket Ground|Lords']] [[Test cricket|Test match]] against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]], in May 2007, to show their support for Madeleine. A picture of Madeleine was also shown on the big screen at the match.<ref>{{Cite news | title = England cricket team join support to help find Madeleine |work=Daily Mail |location=UK | date = 25 May 2007 | url = http://www.mailonsunday.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/news.html?in_article_id=457713&in_page_id=1770 | accessdate = 26 May 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===From education===\nTo further publicise Madeleine's disappearance, the [[Student|pupils]] of [[Bishop Ellis Catholic Primary School]], the school that she would have attended from September 2007, lined up in the school's [[playground]] on 18 June to spell out ''Find Madeleine''. This was easily readable from the air.{{cn|date=January 2020}} In August the school announced that they had saved a desk, coat peg and locker for the child.<ref>{{Cite news | title = A peg for Maddy | work = The Daily Mirror | location = UK | date = 19 August 2007 | url = https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/topstories/2007/08/18/a-peg-for-maddy-89520-19655192/ | accessdate = 28 August 2007 }}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | title = Empty seat for Maddie on first day at school | work = Daily Express | location = UK | date = 31 August 2007 | url = http://www2.dailyexpress.co.uk/posts/view/17756/Madeleine's-school-seat-left-empty | archive-url = https://archive.is/20070928134705/http://www2.dailyexpress.co.uk/posts/view/17756/Madeleine's-school-seat-left-empty | url-status = dead | archive-date = 28 September 2007 | accessdate = 31 August 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n\n===Of the public and political reaction===\nThe scale of the public reaction provoked negative comment from a number of media commentators. On 16 May 2007 on [[BBC Radio 4]], [[Matthew Parris]] said that politicians' displays of concern were \"hollow\". He also claimed that politicians \"read the common newspapers and they decide this is what the common people feel, and they get all caught up with it. But it's all to do with trying to associate themselves with the common herd and they're not part of it. They're politicians\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/index.php?menuID=1&subID=1407 |title=There's something hollow about it |author=Matthew Parris |work=[[The First Post]] |date=16 May 2007 |accessdate=31 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070523055235/http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/index.php?menuID=1&subID=1407 |archivedate=23 May 2007 |author-link=Matthew Parris }}</ref> He went on to say, in his column on 17 May, that [[Member of Parliament|MPs]] wearing yellow ribbons was mawkish and an attempt to \"tap in to the emotions of the mob\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/matthew_parris/article1801174.ece|title=Now no one will realise that I'm nuts about Hazel|author=Matthew Parris|work=The Times |location=UK|date=17 May 2007|accessdate = 19 May 2007 |author-link=Matthew Parris}}</ref> Then on 19 May, ''[[The Guardian]]'' described the public reaction as hysteria and drew a parallel with the response to the ''[[News of the World]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Pedophilia|anti-paedophile]] campaign.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Emma |last=Brockes |authorlink=Emma Brockes |author=|title=In chatrooms and message boards, Madeleine hysteria grips the world |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk_news/story/0,,2083248,00.html |work=The Guardian |location=UK |id= |pages= |page= |date=19 May 2007|accessdate=19 May 2007 |language= }}</ref>\n\nWriting in [[The Times]] on 16 September, [[India Knight]] criticised the on-line community for its censorious attitude and its willingness to rush to judgement whilst pointing out that the McCanns had contributed to the public's obsession with the case by their extensive and well-orchestrated media campaign.<ref>{{Cite news |author=India Knight |title=Madeleine McCann: You are all guilty |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article2459924.ece |work=The Times |location=UK |date=16 September 2007 |accessdate=6 December 2007 |author-link=India Knight }}</ref> A debate on the disappearance was held at the [[London School of Economics]] on 30 January 2008. Although the debate was inconclusive, the stridently critical attitude of the on-line community towards the McCanns, noted by Knight, also manifested itself in the audience reaction.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Roy Greenslade |title=The McCanns' debate: from banality to an outpouring of bile |url=http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/greenslade/2008/01/the_mccanns_debate_from_banali.html |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=31 January 2008 |accessdate=1 February 2008 |author-link=Roy Greenslade }}</ref>\n\n===Of the media coverage===\n\n====Importance of the coverage====\nSome have suggested that the high level of media coverage could be [[Missing white woman syndrome|attributable to Madeleine's race, nationality, or socio-economic status]].<!-- According to [[UNICEF]] (the UN children's fund), 1.2&nbsp;million children are trafficked every year around the world. --> ''[[The Independent]]'', in an editorial on 15 May 2007, described the media coverage as showing a warped sense of priorities and condemned the criticism of the Portuguese authorities as [[jingoism]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://comment.independent.co.uk/leading_articles/article2542346.ece|title=Wild theories and a warped sense of priorities|author=Editorial|work=The Independent|date=15 May 2007|accessdate=19 May 2007|location=London|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070517042757/http://comment.independent.co.uk/leading_articles/article2542346.ece|archivedate=17 May 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In his 17 May column in Portugal's ''[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]'' newspaper, the former head of Portugal's bar association, Jos\u00e9 Miguel J\u00fadice, said the enormous mobilisation was because the little girl \"is English, white, and the daughter of doctors.\"<ref name=IPS>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=37797 |title=Some Missing Children More Equal than Others |author=Mario de Queiroz |publisher=[[Inter Press Service]] |date=18 May 2007 |accessdate=19 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070613144404/http://www.ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=37797 |archivedate=13 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May, ''[[Inter Press Service]]'' drew attention to the fact that some observers point out that Madeleine comes from a well-heeled British family (both of her parents are doctors), unlike so many Portuguese or immigrant children whose disappearance has drawn scant attention from the press.<ref name=IPS/> There has also been criticism of the weight put on this case in the light of many other, unpublicised, children's disappearances.<ref name=\"IPS\"/>\n\nAlso on 18 May, ''[[The Scotsman]]'' commented that \"... there was evidence that public opinion, while strongly supportive of the child's distraught parents Kate and Gerry McCann, was growing alarmed at what it viewed as relentless, almost prurient coverage.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Baker |first=Luke |title=Has Britain gone overboard for missing Madeleine? |work=The Scotsman |location=UK |date=18 May 2007 |url=http://news.scotsman.com/latest.cfm?id=776102007 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120731022402/http://news.scotsman.com/latest.cfm?id=776102007 |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 July 2012 |accessdate=23 May 2007 }}</ref> [[Channel 4 News]] presenter [[Alex Thomson (journalist)|Alex Thomson]] has said the Madeleine McCann story did not deserve its news ranking. \"I've been sickened by the way the media have allowed themselves to be taken for a full-scale ride by the McCanns.\" He added that the parents' conduct, \"a contributory factor in the abduction, was largely downplayed or ignored altogether by sycophantic, gullible blanket coverage.\"<ref>{{Cite news\n |last=Thomson \n |first=Alex \n |title=Paris Hilton? Not on my watch! \n |work=[[Press Gazette]] \n |date=6 July 2007 \n |url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=6&storycode=38152&c=1 \n |accessdate=6 July 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070709114545/http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=6&storycode=38152&c=1 \n |archivedate= 9 July 2007 \n}}</ref>\n\nRaymond Snoddy wrote in ''Marketing'': \"To what extent has all this coverage been kept afloat for so long because the child is white and photogenic, and has articulate, resourceful parents? Of course, the news value of the story was also enhanced by context - everyone's worst nightmare, a child snatched from an apparently secure apartment in an upmarket holiday resort. But the sad truth is that if a black child had been snatched from a [[sink estate]] in Liverpool or Glasgow, the chances are you would not know their name.\"<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Snoddy\n | first = Raymond\n | title = Was TV coverage right for Madeleine?\n |work=Marketing\n | date = 13 June 2007\n | page = 20\n | id = {{ProQuest|214980219}}\n }}</ref>\n\nGerry, who had encouraged media coverage, criticised ''[[De Telegraaf]]'' on 14 June for publishing a letter<ref name=\"BBCletter\">{{Cite news | title = Madeleine police probing letter |publisher=BBC News | date = 13 June 2007 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6749131.stm | accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref> claiming to know the [[Disappearance of Madeleine McCann#Other lines of enquiry|location of Madeleine's body]], calling it \"an irresponsible piece of journalism\" and \"insensitive and cruel\".<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Siddique\n | first = Haroon\n | title = Madeleine's parents condemn publication of letter\n |work=The Guardian\n | date = 14 June 2007\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/crime/article/0,,2103138,00.html?gusrc=rss&feed=11\n | accessdate = 14 June 2007\n| location=London}}</ref> Portuguese police searched the site but found no trace of Madeleine.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Reis\n | first = Paolo\n | title = Detectives' hunt for Madeleine 'was illegal'\n |work=The Times |location=UK\n | date = 25 August 2007\n | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article2324229.ece\n | accessdate = 1 September 2007}}</ref> At the [[Edinburgh International Television Festival]] on 25 August, Gerry complained about the amount of media attention, on the disappearance, that he claimed was 10 times what he had expected. He also criticised wild speculation being erroneously reported as fact.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Kelbie\n | first = Paul\n | title = Madeleine's father appeals for restraint by the media\n |work=The Observer |location=UK\n | date = 26 August 2007\n | url = http://observer.guardian.co.uk/uk_news/story/0,,2156496,00.html\n | accessdate = 26 August 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThere was criticism by the ''[[Daily Express]]'' of the stories run in the Portuguese media. In an article on 28 August that summarised the speculation, the ''Daily Express'' accused the local media of \"a vile whispering campaign, which has led to them [the McCanns] suffering a daily torrent of smears\" and described the stories suggesting that the McCanns had involvement in their daughter's disappearance as \"lies\".<ref>{{Cite news\n |last        = Flanagan\n |first       = Padraic\n |title       = McCanns Rocked By Stream Of Vicious Smears\n |work        = Daily Express\n |location    = UK\n |date        = 28 August 2007\n |url         = http://www2.dailyexpress.co.uk/posts/view/17504/McCanns-rocked-by-stream-of-vicious-smears\n |accessdate  = 29 August 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://archive.is/20070928134727/http://www2.dailyexpress.co.uk/posts/view/17504/McCanns-rocked-by-stream-of-vicious-smears\n |archivedate = 28 September 2007\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nJournalist [[Martin Bell]] accused the [[BBC]] of wasting hundreds of thousands of pounds of taxpayers' money in its coverage of the disappearance. In January 2008 Bell said \"I'm calling it the death of news. It is the stupidification of the news agenda. It is pretty obvious television news has lost its way not just with the McCann case but that has been extreme.\"<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Nicole\n | first = Martin\n | title = BBC 'wasted money' covering McCann case\n |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK\n | date = 16 January 2008\n | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2008/01/16/nbbc116.xml\n | accessdate = 16 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\nA comparison was drawn, in early March 2008, between the publicity given to Madeleine with the much lower key publicity for the [[disappearance of Shannon Matthews]]. [[The Guardian]] explained this by stating that \"Overarching everything is social class\" but they added that Shannon going missing in the UK made a difference. [[The Independent]] took the same line saying \"Kate and Gerry McCann had a lot: they were a couple of nice middle-class doctors on holiday in an upmarket resort\" \"Karen Matthews is not as elegant, nor as eloquent\".<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Greenslade\n | first = Roy\n | title = Why is missing Shannon not getting the same coverage as Madeleine?\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 5 March 2008\n | url = http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/greenslade/2008/03/why_is_missing_shannon_not_get.html\n | accessdate = 5 March 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Nicole\n | first = Martin\n | title = Missing: The contrasting searches for Shannon and Madeleine\n |work=The Independent |location=UK\n | date = 2 March 2008\n | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/missing-the-contrasting-searches-for-shannon-and-madeleine-790207.html\n | accessdate = 5 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn his book [[Spoilt Rotten: The Toxic Cult of Sentimentality|''Spoilt Rotten'']] [[Theodore Dalrymple]] analyses critically the media attention and reaction to the disappearance, and specifically how certain elements in the media interpreted the lack of emotion displayed by the girl's parents as evidence of guilt.<ref>{{Cite book\n  |ref=harv\n  |last= Dalrymple\n  |first= Theodore\n  |title=Spoilt Rotten: The Toxic Cult of Sentimentality\n  |publisher=Gibson Square Books Ltd\n  |year=2010\n  |isbn=978-1-906142-61-2\n  |page=138|title-link= Spoilt Rotten: The Toxic Cult of Sentimentality\n }}</ref>\n\n====Objectivity of the coverage====\nIn an interview published on 1 July [[Martin Brunt]], a [[Sky News]] journalist who had covered the case extensively, conceded that the media's handling of the Madeleine McCann disappearance had been flawed. \"It's the view of a few of us that when we look back over the first two or three weeks of the coverage we were in some ways over-sympathetic. We kind of adopted the tone and the language that the family did. I think we perhaps lost our objectivity a bit, we became a bit too subjective about the story.\"<ref>{{Cite news\n |last        = Brunt\n |first       = Martin\n |title       = Brunt of the Yard presents his case\n |work        = The Independent\n |location    = UK\n |date        = 2 July 2007\n |url         = http://news.independent.co.uk/media/article2725892.ece\n |accessdate  = 2 July 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070706231113/http://news.independent.co.uk/media/article2725892.ece\n |archivedate = 6 July 2007\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nThe British media has been criticised for being heavily critical of the Portuguese police and legal system.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Jenkins\n | first = Simon\n | title = The British media does not do responsibility. It does stories\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 18 May 2007\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/story/0,,2082507,00.html\n | accessdate = 10 September 2007 }}</ref> ''The Guardian'' noted that the British media compared the Portuguese procedures with British procedures unfavourably and unfairly.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Berlins\n | first = Marcel\n | title = Media have rushed to judge Portuguese police\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 10 September 2007\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/law/story/0,,2165920,00.html\n | accessdate = 10 September 2007 }}</ref>\nLikewise, ''[[The Times]]'' published an editorial titled \"Exactly how guilty are the Portuguese police?\" and stated that there had been a rush to judge the Portuguese authorities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hume |first=Mick |title=Exactly how guilty are the Portuguese police? |work=The Times |location=UK |date=11 September 2007 |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/mick_hume/article2426174.ece |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505100731/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/mick_hume/article2426174.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 May 2013 |accessdate=11 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\nMatthew Parris, writing for ''The Times'' in August, chastised the British and Portuguese media for what he described as \"assassination-by-innuendo\" of suspect Robert Murat, who those involved closely in the case believed was innocent. \"For the rest of the world, however, glancing in passing at headlines and skimming news reports over its coffee, the name Murat is now synonymous with 'creepy oddball and obvious suspect',\" Parris wrote. He concluded, \"The whole disgusting business, the whole media-driven infatuation with this little girl and her parents, the whole sick, morbid, sentimental campaign of news generation and news manipulation, has been a disgrace to the British media.\"<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Parris\n | first = Matthew\n | authorlink = Matthew Parris\n | title = The forgotten victim in the McCann case\n |work=The Times |location=UK\n | date = 25 August 2007\n | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/matthew_parris/article2324200.ece\n | accessdate = 11 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Horrocks]], the head of [[BBC]] TV News, denied claims in September 2007 that the BBC was biased in favour of the McCanns. Some viewers had suggested that the McCanns had been treated in an overly positive light because they were white, middle class doctors.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Borland\n | first = Sophie\n | title = BBC: We are 'not biased' towards Madeleine McCann parents\n |work=The Daily Telegraph\n | date = 12 September 2007\n | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/09/12/nmaddy412.xml\n | accessdate = 12 September 2007\n| location=London}}</ref> Then Horrocks criticised rival [[Broadcasting|broadcasters]], saying \"I know that many other TV and radio networks have been absolutely extraordinary, always talking about it in terms of sympathy and their [McCanns] feelings.\"<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Plunkett\n | first = John\n | title =Horrocks warns on biased McCann reports\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 11 September 2007\n | url = http://media.guardian.co.uk/broadcast/story/0,,2166699,00.html?gusrc=rss&feed=4\n | accessdate = 11 September 2007 }}</ref> Writing in [[The Guardian]], also in September, [[Marcel Berlins]] said that the investigation had generated a wave of negative comments in the UK media towards Portuguese society, and the authorities investigating the case, as the result of ignorance of the [[Portuguese legal system]]. Berlins called it \"a touch of arrogant xenophobia\".<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Berlins\n | first = Marcel\n | title = Media have rushed to judge Portuguese police\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 10 September 2007\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/law/story/0,,2165920,00.html\n | accessdate = 27 November 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Of the publicity===\nIn early July 2007, parents criticised a cinema [[advertising|advertisement]] about the disappearance of Madeleine which showed a still picture of the girl with the statement that she had been \"snatched\" from her room. The advertisement was being screened across Britain before the children's film ''[[Shrek the Third]]'', and parents were complaining to the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]] that it might scare young children and that it detracted from parents' ability to decide how much to tell their children.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Bennett\n | first = Rosemary\n | title = Mothers protest over Madeleine advert before showings of Shrek\n |work=The Times\n | date = 3 July 2007\n | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article2017815.ece\n | accessdate = 3 July 2007\n| location=London}}</ref> Following the protests, the advertisements were quickly withdrawn.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Lane\n | first = Harriet\n | title = The power of mums\n |work=The Times |location=UK\n | date = 5 July 2007\n | url = http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/families/article2026302.ece\n | accessdate = 5 July 2007 }}</ref> Subsequently, however, the advertisement, which had received a [[British Board of Film Classification]] to be aired in U-certificate films, was cleared by the Advertising Standards Authority.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Sweney\n | first = Mark\n | title = Madeleine cinema ad cleared\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 22 August 2007\n | url = http://media.guardian.co.uk/advertising/story/0,,2153412,00.html\n | accessdate = 24 August 2007 }}</ref>\n\nA plan to include [[bookmark]]s bearing Madeleine's image in copies of ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows]]'' was shelved. After reflection, the [[Publishing|publishers]] decided it would not be responsible to expose younger readers to the story of Madeleine's disappearance.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = Harry Potter used in worldwide appeal to help find missing Madeleine\n |work=Daily Mail |location=UK\n | date = 17 July 2007\n | url = http://www.mailonsunday.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/news.html?in_article_id=468931&in_page_id=1770\n | accessdate = 18 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nWhilst the public response has largely been in support of the Find Maddie campaign, there have been instances where it has been criticised for drawing attention away from other missing children.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = O'Hanlon\n | first = Ellis\n | title = Sorry to bore you, but Maddy is still missing\n | publisher=The Irish Independent\n | date = 3 June 2007\n | url = http://www.independent.ie/unsorted/features/sorry-to-bore-you-but-maddy-is-still-missing-690670.html\n | accessdate = 9 September 2007}}</ref> Mark Lawson, writing in [[The Guardian]] on 26 October, criticised the McCanns for employing their own [[Spin (public relations)|spin doctor]], describing their use of what he termed \"political methods\" as a \"terrible error\".<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Lawson\n | first = Mark\n | title = Spin is not the answer\n |work=The Guardian | date = 26 October 2007\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/comment/story/0,,2199439,00.html\n | accessdate = 27 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nCarlos Anjos, president of the ''Association of Criminal Investigation Staff'', criticised the McCanns, on 6 November, for creating a \"monster of information\" that hindered the investigation. He also stated that they should not have publicised the [[coloboma]] in her right eye which he claimed put the life of the girl at risk.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Brown\n | first = David\n | title = Kate and Gerry McCann 'created information monster' that hindered search for Madeleine McCann\n | work=The Times\n | date = 6 November 2007\n | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article2820330.ece\n | accessdate = 7 November 2007 }}</ref> This was echoed by Fernando Jos\u00e9 Pinto Monteiro, the [[Attorney General]], who said that, if she had been abducted, the worldwide campaign would have turned Madeleine into a liability and that it was likely that her abductor had already killed her.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Govan\n | first = Fiona\n | title = Madeleine McCann is probably dead\n | publisher=The Daily Telegraph\n | date = 23 November 2007\n | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/11/23/wmaddy123.xml\n | accessdate = 24 November 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Rewards==\nRewards offered totalled over \u00a32.6&nbsp;million including:\n* [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1,500,000 ([[Euro|\u20ac]]2,200,000) including [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]250,000 by the ''[[News of the World]]'', [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]250,000 by [[Sir Philip Green]], [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]50,000 by [[Simon Cowell]] and [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]25,000 by [[Coleen McLoughlin]]. Other contributors include [[Sir Richard Branson]], [[JK Rowling]], and [[Bill Kenwright]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6649951.stm|title=Madeleine reward rises to \u00a32.5m|publisher=BBC|date=12 May 2007|accessdate = 12 May 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,91210-1265397,00.html |title=Rewards For Madeleine Info Top \u00a32.5m |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=12 May 2007 |accessdate=12 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070515162520/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0%2C%2C91210-1265397%2C00.html |archivedate=15 May 2007 }}</ref>\n* [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1,000,000 (\u20ac1,470,000) by British businessman [[Stephen Winyard]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/6642115.stm|title=\u00a31m reward over missing Madeleine|publisher=BBC News|date=11 May 2007|accessdate = 11 May 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/news/article.html?in_article_id=48582&in_page_id=34|title=\u00a31m reward in hunt for Maddie|publisher=[[Metro (Associated Metro Limited)|The Metro]]|date=10 May 2007|accessdate = 10 May 2007}}</ref>\n* [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]100,000 (\u20ac147,000) by a colleague of Kate McCann.<ref name=\"Sky story\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-1264342,00.html |title=Continue To Pray For Madeleine |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=6 May 2007 |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070508050600/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0%2C%2C30100-1264342%2C00.html |archivedate= 8 May 2007 }}</ref>\n* [[Euro|\u20ac]]15,000 (\u00a310,250) by Portuguese newspaper ''[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.record.pt/noticia.asp?id=744701&idCanal=127 |title=Record oferece 15.000 euros |work=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]] |date=12 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929122204/http://www.record.pt/noticia.asp?id=744701&idCanal=127 |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"cnubarrister\">{{cite news |date=2014-11-14 |title=Shrimpton: Barrister claims missing Maddie held on boat |url=http://courtnewsuk.co.uk/shrimpton-barrister-claims-missing-maddie-held-on-boat/ |author=<!-- Staff writers; no byline --> |newspaper=Court News UK |accessdate=2016-09-24}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"cnubomb\">{{cite news |date=2014-11-19 |title=Shrimpton: Bomb scare barrister says: 'I'm not a nutter' |url=http://courtnewsuk.co.uk/shrimptonbomb-scare-barrister-says-im-not-a-nutter/ |author=<!-- Staff writers; no byline --> |newspaper=Court News UK |accessdate=2016-09-24}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"nazi\">{{cite news |author=<!-- Staff writers; no byline --> |newspaper=[[The Scotsman]] |title=Barrister jailed for Nazi Olympics bomb hoax call |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/uk/barrister-jailed-for-nazi-olympics-bomb-hoax-call-1-3682715 |date=2015-02-06 |accessdate=2016-09-19}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n\n[[Category:Disappearance of Madeleine McCann]]\n[[Category:International responses to media-related events|McCann, Madeleine]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|Sightings of Madeleine McCann}}\n{{Main|Disappearance of Madeleine McCann}}\n[[File:Madeleine FA Cup Final 2007.jpg|right|300px|thumb|<center>Appeal at the [[FA Cup Final 2007|2007 FA Cup Final]]</center>]]\nOn the evening of Thursday, 3 May 2007, shortly before her fourth birthday, a [[British people|British]] child, Madeleine McCann, went missing from a holiday apartment in [[Praia da Luz]] in the [[Algarve]] in Portugal, in which she was staying with her parents.\n\nThe Portuguese police investigation into her disappearance closed in July 2008. [[Scotland Yard]] in May 2011 began a review of the case , [[Operation Grange]], and in April 2012 announced their belief that Madeleine might still be alive.<ref>{{cite news |title=Madeleine McCann 'could be alive' say detectives as new image released |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=25 April 2012 |accessdate=25 April 2012 |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/madeleinemccann/9225661/Madeleine-McCann-could-be-alive-say-detectives-as-new-image-released.html}}</ref>\n\nIn the weeks following her disappearance, Madeleine's parents implemented a successful [[#By the family|publicity campaign]] that kept her in the public eye. This resulted in a wide-reaching international response, both in the media and by the public, which led to some criticism that the [[#Of the media coverage|media attention]] was excessive. There was also comment that the UK media had unfairly [[#Objectivity of the coverage|criticised the Portuguese police]].\n\n==Publicity==\n\n===By the family===\n\nAn official website for the search was set up, and the McCann family broadcast two early video appeals.<ref>{{Cite web | title = News Items | work=findmadeleine.com | publisher=McCann Family | date = 21 May 2007 | url = http://www.findmadeleine.com/news/ | accessdate = 21 May 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070519053412/http://www.findmadeleine.com/news/ |archivedate = 19 May 2007}}</ref> The first was a photograph and video montage set to [[Simple Minds]]' song \"[[Don't You (Forget About Me)]]\" and included an animation of the word LOOK in [[uppercase]] with a reproduction of her [[coloboma]] as a radial line inside the first letter O, which blinks.<ref>{{Cite video|people=Madeline McCann |title=Picture Video |publisher=McCann Family, [[Sky News]] |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/video/videoplayer/0,,31200-1266128,00.html |date=18 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070618174409/http://news.sky.com/skynews/video/videoplayer/0%2C%2C31200-1266128%2C00.html |archivedate=18 June 2007 }}</ref> The second featured a montage of images with a voice-over by actress [[Zo\u00eb Wanamaker]] mentioning her coloboma, seeking information about her whereabouts, and asking people to download and display a poster of her from the official site.<ref>{{Cite video|people=Madeline McCann, [[Zo\u00eb Wanamaker]] (voice) |title=Video Appeal |publisher=McCann Family, [[Sky News]] |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/video/videoplayer/0,,31200-1266568,00.html |date=21 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609095553/http://news.sky.com/skynews/video/videoplayer/0%2C%2C31200-1266568%2C00.html |archivedate= 9 June 2007 }}</ref>\n \nThe family said that part of the money raised from [[#Madeleine's Fund|Madeleine's Fund]] would go towards hiring professional campaigners, with a view to achieving the same saturation level of publicity across Europe as had been attained in the UK and the [[Algarve]].<ref>{{Cite news | last = Tremlett | first = Giles | title = Multinationals get behind hunt for Madeleine |work=The Guardian | date = 18 May 2007 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/crime/article/0,,2082626,00.html#article_continue | accessdate = 3 June 2007 | location=London}}</ref> The family based themselves in the same holiday resort from the time of the disappearance and stated then that they would not leave until Madeleine was located. Though as the campaign progressed, they ended up visiting   the Vatican City, Spain, Germany, and Morocco for it, and on 5 June, they made an appeal on the British TV programme ''[[Crimewatch]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Ian Herbert|title=Madeleine 'sightings' mount as the agony goes on and on|url=http://news.independent.co.uk/europe/article2562745.ece|work=The Independent|date=20 May 2007|accessdate=21 May 2007|location=London|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070707202709/http://news.independent.co.uk/europe/article2562745.ece|archivedate=7 July 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Edwards | first = Richard | title = No answers as McCanns' campaign marches on |work=The Daily Telegraph | date = 6 June 2007 | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/06/06/nmaddy106.xml | accessdate = 6 June 2007 | location=London}}</ref> However, shortly after being named as [[arguido]]s, the McCanns returned to the UK on 9 September.<ref name=\"journey begun\">{{Cite news | title = Madeleine parents head back to UK |publisher=BBC News | date = 9 September 2007 |accessdate = 9 September 2007 |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6985454.stm}}</ref>\n\nMadeleine's father had already made a brief trip to the UK, on 20 May 2007, to help finalise the campaign for the search for his daughter.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Madeleine's father returns to UK |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk_news/story/0,,2084699,00.html |work=The Guardian |id= |pages= |page= |date=21 May 2007 |accessdate=21 May 2007 |language= |quote= | location=London}}</ref> Gerry McCann visited the United States between 22 and 25 July when he met [[United States Attorney General|US Attorney General]] [[Alberto Gonzales]] and experts from the National and International Centres for Missing and Exploited Children. During interviews on [[Television network|network television]] programmes Gerry was forced to defend leaving the children alone.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Moult | first = Julie | title = Madeleine's father quizzed over decision to leave her on her own |work=[[Daily Mail|Mail on Sunday]] | date = 25 July 2007 | url = http://www.mailonsunday.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/news.html?in_article_id=470179&in_page_id=1770 | accessdate = 26 July 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe family announced on 15 September 2007 that, beginning in a fortnight, they would be spending up to \u00a380,000, from [[#Madeleine's Fund|Madeleine's Fund]], on a new publicity drive, involving newspaper, television, and [[poster]] advertising to further publicise Madeleine's disappearance.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Push for Madeleine ad publicity |publisher=BBC | date = 15 September 2007 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/6996560.stm | accessdate = 16 September 2007 }}</ref> This will include posters in rural parts of Portugal and Spain and television advertisements, in Arabic, in Morocco.<ref>{{Cite news | author=Mark Townsend and James Robinson| title = Arabic advertisements aid Madeleine hunt |work=The Observer | date = 30 September 2007 | url = http://observer.guardian.co.uk/world/story/0,,2180221,00.html | accessdate = 30 September 2007 | location=London}}</ref> In late October the McCanns set up a [[hotline]] + 34 902 300213, operated by [[Private investigator|private detectives]], for people in the [[Iberian Peninsula]] and North Africa to phone with information.<ref>{{Cite news | title = McCanns set up phone line |work=The Scotsman |location=UK | date = 24 October 2007 | url = http://news.scotsman.com/uk.cfm?id=1696492007 | accessdate = 27 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOver Christmas 2007 the family made a television appeal. This had produced, by 27 December 347 phone calls with information with more subsequently.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Hundreds ring hotline after Madeleine plea |work=The Times | date = 27 December 2007 | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article3095509.ece | accessdate = 27 December 2007 | location=London}}</ref> A further video appeal was made, by the parents, at Christmas 2008. This included footage of Madeleine taken in December 2006.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Christmas appeal for Madeleine |publisher=BBC News | date = 21 December 2008 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/7794194.stm | accessdate = 28 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe parents launched a fresh appeal for information, in March 2009, tightly focused on the area where Madeleine went missing. 10,000 leaflets in Portuguese were distributed in Praia da Luz, [[Lagos, Portugal|Lagos]], and [[Burgau, Portugal|Burgau]] together with billboard advertising.<ref>{{Cite news | title = McCann appeal returns to Portugal |publisher=BBC News | date = 24 March 2009 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/7961734.stm | accessdate = 29 March 2009}}</ref> However, many posters were promptly torn down with [[Correio da Manh\u00e3]] reporting that the local people wanted closure.<ref>{{Cite news | title = New Madeleine Posters Torn Down In Anger | publisher=[[Sky News]] | date = 27 March 2009 | author=Laura Bundock | url = http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/UK-News/Madeleine-McCann-New-Posters-Put-Up-In-Portugal-Are-Torn-Down-By-Angry-Algarve-Residents/Article/200903415249908?lpos=UK_News_News_Your_Way_Region_3&lid=NewsYourWay_ARTICLE_15249908_Madeleine_McCann%3A_New_Posters_Put_Up_In_Portugal_Are_Torn_Down_By_Angry_Algarve_Residents | accessdate = 29 March 2009 }}</ref> The McCanns released an image, on 1 May 2009, of the [[Age progression|projected appearance]] of a 6-year-old Madeleine.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Siddique, Haroon|title=Madeleine McCann's parents release picture of how she might look now|work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2009/may/01/madeleine-mccann-picture|date=1 May 2009|accessdate=16 May 2009 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n===By others===\n[[File:Microsoft.co.uk.png|thumb|right|Advertisement on the front page of [[Microsoft]]'s UK website]]\nSeveral unofficial webpages were created following the disappearance, notably on [[social networking]] sites such as Facebook and MySpace, offering support to the McCanns. An unofficial one minute's silence was held for Madeleine on 21 May 2007<ref name=\"silence\"/>, but since it was organised by an anonymous [[viral email]], it was not thought to be widely observed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://uk.news.yahoo.com/skynews/20070521/tuk-silence-held-for-missing-madeleine-m-45dbed5.html|title=Silence Held For Missing Madeleine McCann|publisher=[[Sky News]]|date=21 May 2007|accessdate=21 May 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070523111013/http://uk.news.yahoo.com/skynews/20070521/tuk-silence-held-for-missing-madeleine-m-45dbed5.html |archivedate = 23 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nRobert Murat, a suspect in the investigation, has tried to generate his own publicity by selling his story. However, [[publicist]] [[Max Clifford]] indicated that he would only represent Murat if he was cleared of suspicion of kidnapping.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gulf-times.com/site/topics/article.asp?cu_no=2&item_no=150786&version=1&template_id=38&parent_id=20 |title=Kidnap suspect looks to cash in on ordeal |work=[[Gulf Times]] |date=23 May 2007 |accessdate=23 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930201329/http://www.gulf-times.com/site/topics/article.asp?cu_no=2&item_no=150786&version=1&template_id=38&parent_id=20 |archivedate=30 September 2007 }}</ref> Within the [[Virtual reality|virtual]] world [[Second Life]], a virtual ''Madeleine's Garden'' has been created.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/index.php?storyID=7096 |title=Inside MaddieWorld |publisher=[[The First Post]] |accessdate=31 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070602112523/http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/index.php?storyID=7096 |archivedate= 2 June 2007 }}</ref> In early July, [[Bryan Adams]] dedicated his concert on Malta to Madeleine.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Singer To Dedicate Gig To Madeleine |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=26 June 2007 |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,91210-1272365,00.html |accessdate=26 June 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629025319/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0%2C%2C91210-1272365%2C00.html |archivedate=29 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\n[[J. K. Rowling]] arranged with her publishers for a poster bearing the face of the missing child to be made available to booksellers when ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows]]'' was launched on 21 July. Rowling said that she hoped that the posters would be displayed prominently in shops all over the world.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Rowling in Madeleine poster plea |publisher=BBC News | date = 16 July 2007| accessdate = 17 July 2007 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/6901845.stm}}</ref>\n\n==Political reaction==\nThe Portuguese Ambassador in London, [[Ant\u00f3nio Santana Carlos]] said on 8 May 2007 that the case was of \"great concern\" to Portugal and asked people to trust the police,<ref name=portugalbbc>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/6635463.stm|title=Portugal defends Madeleine police|publisher=BBC News|accessdate = 8 May 2007 | date=8 May 2007}}</ref> amidst growing criticism of their handling of the case.<ref name=\"mirror criticism\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/topstories/tm_headline=clueless%26method=full%26objectid=19067596%26siteid=89520-name_page.html|title=CLUELESS - We reveal errors made by police in kidnap hunt for Maddy|work=Daily Mirror |location=UK|date=9 May 2007|accessdate = 9 May 2007}}</ref> President [[An\u00edbal Cavaco Silva]] announced on 9 May that he was following the case \"with great concern\", adding that the police were \"doing everything to find the child alive.\"<ref name=iafrica>{{Cite news|url=http://iafrica.com/news/worldnews/844830.htm |title=Video tape may show missing Maddie |publisher=[[iAfrica.com]] |date=9 May 2007 |accessdate=8 June 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070613132814/http://iafrica.com/news/worldnews/844830.htm |archivedate=13 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May, [[Tony Blair]]'s spokesperson said that the then [[Prime minister|Prime Minister]] was following the case closely and that \"we are helping in whatever way we can\".<ref name=iafrica /> On 16 May, coinciding with the launch of [[#Madeline's Fund|the fighting fund]], the then [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] [[Gordon Brown]] delivered a similar message to relatives of Madeleine.<ref name=\"Brownhelp\">{{Cite news | title = Brown offers help over Madeleine |publisher=BBC News | date = 16 May 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6661113.stm| accessdate = 26 May 2007 }}</ref> Former [[Deputy Prime Minister]] [[John Prescott]] also commented on the case, saying at [[Prime Minister's Questions|Prime Minister's Question Time]] \"I'm sure that the thoughts of the whole House will be with them at this terrible time.\"<ref name=\"Brownhelp\" />\n\nOn 26 May, a spokesman for the McCann family confirmed that Gordon Brown had telephoned the McCanns.<ref name=\"browntel\">{{Cite news | title = Brown offers support for McCanns |publisher=BBC News | date = 26 May 2007 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6694999.stm | accessdate = 26 May 2007 }}</ref> Although the spokesman stated that the details of the conversations would remain private, he did confirm that \"During them, Mr Brown offered both Gerry and Kate his full support in their efforts to find Madeleine.\"<ref name=\"browntel\" /> In late September [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] [[David Miliband]] telephoned Gerry.<ref name=\"PI search\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article2558233.ece |title= McCanns send sleuths to Morocco |author=Steven Swinford, John Follainin and Mohamed El Hamraoui |work=The Times |date=30 September 2007|accessdate = 30 September 2007 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n[[Federal Minister of Justice (Germany)|The German Justice Minister]], [[Brigitte Zypries]], said at a meeting of [[G8]] justice ministers in Munich on 3 June, that it should be assumed that Madeleine had been abducted by a gang that passes on children to be abused.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Madeleine paedophile gang theory 'is likely' |work=The Scotsman |location=UK | date = 3 June 2007 | url = http://news.scotsman.com/uk.cfm?id=867592007 | accessdate = 4 June 2007 }}</ref> But the Portuguese prime minister, [[Jos\u00e9 S\u00f3crates]], praised investigators in September 2007, following criticism in the British media of the police handling of the case. S\u00f3crates said that he had total confidence in the work carried out by the Portuguese police.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Madeleine prosecutors seek diaries and toys, reports say |work=The Guardian |author=David Batty, James Sturcke |date = 12 September 2007 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/crime/article/0,,2167511,00.html?gusrc=rss&feed=networkfront | accessdate = 12 September 2007 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Theories by experts==\nThe disappearance provoked differing analyses by experts. Shortly after Madeleine went missing two former [[Scotland Yard]] commanders expressed the view that she had been abducted. Roy Ramm considered that it was a carefully planned kidnapping by someone who had been watching the child.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Britons join search for lost toddler |work=The Times |author=John Follain and Jon Ungoed-Thomas |date = 6 May 2007 | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article1752277.ece |accessdate = 13 October 2007 | location=London}}</ref> John O'Connor was of the view that Madeleine had wandered out of the apartment on her own and was subsequently abducted. O'Connor opined that she was likely to be nearby and recommended a thorough search of surrounding occupied premises.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Madeleine's Eye Holds Vital Clue |work=[[Sky News]] |date=14 May 2007 |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,91210-1265416,00.html |accessdate=13 October 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009032301/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0%2C%2C91210-1265416%2C00.html |archivedate= 9 October 2007 }}</ref> This hypothesis was also supported by criminologist [[Mark Williams-Thomas]] who said, in May 2008, that he believed what happened was that Madeleine woke up, walked around the apartment, found the back patio door was insecure and wandered out. It was at this point that she was most likely abducted by an opportunistic predatory paedophile.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Madeleine: 'My Theories On Missing Girl' | publisher=[[Sky News]] | author=Mark Williams-Thomas | date = 1 May 2008 | accessdate = 25 May 2008 |url = http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30000-1314624,00.html| author-link=Mark Williams-Thomas }}</ref>\n\nHowever Paulo Sargento, a [[Criminal psychology|criminal psychologist]] at [[Universidade Lus\u00f3fona|Lus\u00f3fona University]] in [[Lisbon]], had produced in October 2007 a 3D reconstruction of events at the Ocean Club on the evening Madeleine disappeared, and his view was that kidnapping would be inconsistent with the evidence.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Reconstruction 'casts doubt on Madeleine McCann kidnapping' |work=The Times |author=David Brown |date = 9 October 2007 | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/article2622152.ece |accessdate = 12 October 2007 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title = Desaparecimento de Madeleine McCann |work=Videos.sapos |date = 8 October 2007 | url=https://videos.sapo.pt/wvhISANaAzuzEqRpe6Iz |accessdate = 12 October 2007}}</ref> The case was also reviewed by the notable forensic investigator Professor [[David Barclay (academic)|David Barclay]] of [[Robert Gordon University]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.rgu.ac.uk/news/disp_NewsPreview.cfm?PGE_ID=42071&vmenu=2 |title=World renowned forensic investigator and 'Waking the Dead' advisor joins RGU |publisher=[[Robert Gordon University]]|date=3 April 2007|accessdate = 20 October 2007}}</ref> His opinion was that the police were right to consider the McCanns as suspects and that the child is probably dead.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stv.tv/content/news/headlines/display.html?id=opencms:/news/Forensics_expert_defends_Portugese_police_involved_in_Madeleine_case |title=Forensic expert defends Portuguese police involved in Madeleine case |publisher=[[STV (TV network)|STV]] |date=n.d. |accessdate=15 October 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071225204145/http://www.stv.tv/content/news/headlines/display.html?id=opencms%3A%2Fnews%2FForensics_expert_defends_Portugese_police_involved_in_Madeleine_case |archivedate=25 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Comparison and possible relations with the murder of Joana Cipriano==\n{{See also|Murder of Joana Cipriano}}\nJoana Cipriano, a then 8-year-old girl, disappeared on 12 September 2004 from the village of Figueira, only seven miles from [[Praia da Luz]], where Madeleine McCann disappeared on 3 May 2007.<ref name=Watts14Sep2007>{{cite news |last=Watts |first=Alex |date=14 September 2007 |title=Girl's Case 'May Solve McCann Mystery |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,91210-1283987,00.html |url-status=dead |language=English |work=[[Sky News]] |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009185533/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,91210-1283987,00.html |archive-date=9 October 2007 |access-date=14 October 2017 |via=[[Internet Archive]] [[Wayback Machine]]}}</ref> In both cases, the mothers launched campaigns to find their daughters and, in both cases, the local ''Pol\u00edcia Judici\u00e1ria'' investigated the possibility that the mothers had killed their daughters.<ref name=Govan26May2007>{{cite news |last=Govan |first=Fiona |date=28 May 2007 |title=The detectives working as the world watches |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1552718/The-detectives-working-as-the-world-watches.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London |access-date=14 October 2017}}\n*{{cite book |last=Collins |first=Danny |date=2008 |title=Vanished: The Truth about the Disappearance of Madeleine McCann |url=https://books.google.com/?id=iHhVLQAACAAJ |location= |publisher=[[John Blake (journalist)#John Blake Publishing|John Blake Publishing]] |page= |isbn=978-1844546145 |author-link= }} (Note: paperback edition).</ref>\n\nA child protection specialist, Mark Williams-Thomas, who believes that Joana's and Madeleine's disappearances are related, said that the disappearance of two children unknown to each other, within a period of four years in a seven-mile radius, would be a huge coincidence, especially considering that Portugal is a small country with few abductions.<ref name=Watts14Sep2007/> Before Joana's disappearance, the previous first-degree murder of a child in the [[Algarve]] region was in November 1990 and involved a British girl, nine-year-old Rachel Charles, who was abducted and murdered in [[Albufeira]]. Her body was found three days later; a British mechanic, Michael Cook, a friend of the family, was arrested and convicted.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tweedie |first1=Neil |last2=Edwards |first2=Richard |date=12 May 2007 |title=Have police failed Madeleine? |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1551346/Have-police-failed-Madeleine.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London |access-date=14 October 2017 }}\n*On 19 June 1996 a six-year-old German child, Ren\u00e8 Has\u00e8e, also disappeared, from the Amoreira beach near [[Aljezur]] while walking a few metres ahead of his parents; see [http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/2075dmprt.html The Doe Network: Case File 2075DMPRT] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080508221139/http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/2075dmprt.html |date=8 May 2008 }} and [http://en.sevenload.com/photos/Qxy8SOM-Rene-Hasee-vermisst-seit-dem-19-Juni-1996 \"Rene Hasee vermisst seit dem 19.Juni 1996\"]{{dead link|date=June 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}.</ref> Leandro Silva, the [[Common-law marriage|common-law husband]] of Leonor Cipriano, said in 2007 that \"the only difference between the McCanns and us is that we don't have money.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Antezana |first=Fabiola |date=26 September 2007 |title=Detective in McCann Case Investigated For Beating Convicted Child Murderer |url=http://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/story?id=3646987&page=1#.UZeqSoIilDQ |work=[[ABC News]] |location=New York City |access-date=14 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nSeveral similarities between the cases\u2014both girls vanished without trace within {{convert|7|mi}} and less than three years of each other, in both cases officers failed to secure the crime scene, both mothers mounted campaigns to find their daughters and both women were accused of involvement\u2014prompted Joana's family to appeal in 2008 for police to investigate whether there was a link between the disappearances.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Watts |first1=Alex |date=12 May 2008 |title='Disturbing Similarities' With Madeleine |url=http://news.sky.com/story/603144/disturbing-similarities-with-madeleine |url-status=dead |language=English |work=[[Sky News]] |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234140/http://news.sky.com/story/603144/disturbing-similarities-with-madeleine |archive-date=3 March 2016 |access-date=October 14, 2017 |via=[[Internet Archive]] [[Wayback Machine]]}}</ref>\n\n==Fundraising==\n\n===Madeleine's Fund===\nA fundraising company, known as ''Madeleine's Fund: Leaving No Stone Unturned'', was launched in [[Leicester]] on 16 May 2007. The Fund is a limited company, not a [[Charitable organization|registered charity]], because its objectives are not wide enough to satisfy [[Charity Commission]] criteria for UK charities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/09/11/wmaddy1011.xml|title=McCanns may use Madeleine fund for defence\n|work=Daily Telegraph |date=12 September 2007|accessdate = 12 September 2007 | location=London | first=Nick | last=Britten}}</ref> The objectives include helping the extended family with their expenses (to prevent abuse, payments can only be authorised by the independent members of the board who are not family members) and continuing the investigation independently should that prove necessary. Any excess funds would be used to help search for other abducted children.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6662723.stm|title=Madeleine fighting fund launched|publisher=BBC News|date=16 May 2007|accessdate = 16 May 2007}}</ref> The Fund's website reportedly received 58&nbsp;million [[Hit (web request)|hits]] and 16,000 messages of support by 18 May, only two days after its launch.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6668479.stm|title=Madeleine film plan for Cup Final|date=18 May 2007|publisher=BBC News|accessdate = 18 May 2007}}</ref> Over \u00a31,095,000 had been raised by 30 October 2007.<ref>[http://www.bringmadeleinehome.com/news/fund.asp ''Madeleine's Fund: Leaving No Stone Unturned''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070606145016/http://www.bringmadeleinehome.com/news/fund.asp |date=6 June 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"mortgage payments\"/> Two \u00a32,000 monthly re-payments on the McCanns' [[Mortgage loan|mortgage]] were made from the Fund in July and August.<ref name=\"mortgage payments\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/10/30/wmaddy230.xml |title=McCanns used \u00a31m fund to pay mortgage |author=Caroline Gammell\n|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK|date=31 October 2007|accessdate = 20 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Legal costs funding===\nThe trustees of ''Madeleine's Fund'' announced in September that the fund would not be used to pay the McCanns' legal costs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article2441844.ece |title=Parents will have to pay defence costs without Madeleine's Fund |author=Adam Fresco, Patrick Foster and Fran Yeoman |work=The Times |location=UK|date=13 September 2007|accessdate = 13 September 2007 }}</ref> Initially, the McCanns considered setting up a separate appeal fund for legal expenses.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Adam Fresco and David Brown |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article2439634.ece| title=Madeleine's parents consider new fund for legal battle |work=The Times |location=UK|date=12 September 2007|accessdate = 12 September 2007 }}</ref> However, [[Richard Branson]] created a fund for the McCann's legal expenses, including those of their current advisor, [[Michael Caplan]] [[Queen's Counsel|QC]], a solicitor and partner in the London firm of Kingsley Napley.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6997429.stm|title=Branson fund for McCanns' lawyers |publisher=BBC News|date=16 September 2007|accessdate = 16 September 2007}}</ref> [[Stephen Winyard]] came out in December as having contributed \u00a3100,000 to the McCanns' defence fund, which paid for [[Genetic fingerprinting|DNA tests]] carried out on the [[Renault Sc\u00e9nic]] hire car used by the McCanns.<ref name=\"Stephen Winyard\"/> He also revealed [[Brian Kennedy (businessman)|Brian Kennedy]] as another donor.<ref name=\"Stephen Winyard\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.scotsman.com/scotland.cfm?id=1914972007 |title=Scots tycoon attacks 'scurrilous allegations' as he comes out as McCanns' secret funder |author=Michael Howie |work=The Scotsman |location=UK|date=8 December 2007|accessdate = 9 December 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Potential frauds==\nMany unofficial websites were registered which had domain names that contained slight misspellings of Madeleine's name (a practice known as [[typosquatting]]), plus keywords likely to be used in searches. These websites contained material unrelated to Madeleine.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Mills | first = James |author2=Greenhill, Sam  |author3=Rees, Gwyneth | title = Sick web hijackers cash in on Madeleine |work=Daily Mail |location=UK | date = 19 May 2007 | url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/news.html?in_article_id=455885&in_page_id=1770 | accessdate = 22 May 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThere have also been people collecting money on the [[false premise]] that they were representing [[Response to the disappearance of Madeleine McCann#Madeleine's Fund|Madeleine's Fund]], one of whom, Debbie Clifton, was jailed for 90 days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/staffordshire/6284516.stm|title=AMadeleine cash theft woman jailed |publisher=BBC News|date=9 July 2007|accessdate=10 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 June 2007 police arrested an Italian man and a Portuguese woman at a villa in [[Sotogrande]], [[C\u00e1diz]] over allegations that they had tried to defraud the McCanns by claiming a reward for information about their daughter. However, police said that there was no direct link with Madeleine's kidnap.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6251266.stm|title=Italian arrest in Madeleine case|publisher=BBC News|date=28 June 2007|accessdate=28 June 2007}}</ref> Then on 6 July police in the Netherlands arrested a man who allegedly demanded two million euros from the McCanns for information about their missing daughter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article2036933.ece|title=Man held over Madeleine McCann extortion|work=The Times |date=6 July 2007|accessdate=10 July 2007 | location=London | first=David | last=Brown}}</ref>\n\nBritish barrister [[Michael Shrimpton]] presented himself as the \"unofficial representative\" for parents Kate and Gerry McCann, and claimed responsibility for setting up a meeting between them and [[Pope Benedict XVI]].<ref name=\"cnubarrister\" /><ref name=\"cnubomb\" />  According to Shrimpton, Madeleine was being held in or near [[Morocco]] after being smuggled there on a drug-running vessel.<ref name=\"cnubarrister\" /><ref name=\"nazi\" />  Authorities rejected these claims as false and issued a strict warning to Shrimpton not to interfere with the case.<ref name=\"nazi\" /><ref name=\"cnubarrister\" />  Shrimpton was later charged, convicted, and imprisoned for an unrelated hoax.<ref name=\"nazi\" />\n\n==Libel actions==\nThe McCanns announced on 31 August that they were [[Lawsuit|suing]] the Portuguese [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] ''[[Tal & Qual]]'' for [[Slander and libel|libel]]. The newspaper reported that the \"police believe\" that the McCanns killed Madeleine, suggesting she may have died in an accident or from a drugs overdose.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = McCanns to sue Portuguese paper\n |publisher=BBC News\n | date = 31 August 2007\n | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6971662.stm\n | accessdate = 31 August 2007}}</ref> The McCanns' lawyer, Carlos Pinto de Abreu, said the couple's image had been \"dragged through the dirt\" by \"character-assassinating, tabloid-style\" news reports, adding that the press \"has engaged in a horrific exercise in scandal-mongering, replete with rumours and lurid commentaries...to sell more TV time and newspaper space to advertisers\". The police stressed that the McCanns were not suspects.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = McCanns in legal move on newspaper\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 31 August 2007\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uklatest/story/0,,-6888704,00.html\n | accessdate = 31 August 2007\n}} {{Dead link|date=August 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref>\n\n''Tal & Qual'' stood by the story. The journalist who wrote the article, Catarina Vaz Guerreiro, said \"I can't reveal my source, but I have complete trust in them. I strongly believe that the person that gave us this information is telling the truth.\"<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = Top detective in Madeleine inquiry backs 'innocent' McCanns\n |work=Daily Mail |location=UK\n | date = 31 August 2007\n | url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/news.html?in_article_id=478885&in_page_id=1770\n | accessdate = 31 August 2007\n| first=Sam\n| last=Greenhill}}</ref> The paper ceased publication after 28 September 2007, because of a drop in circulation.<ref name=\"publico\">{{Cite news\n |title=Jornal \"Tal & Qual\" acaba amanh\u00e3 \n |publisher=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]] \n |date=27 September 2007 \n |url=http://ultimahora.publico.clix.pt/noticia.aspx?id=1305931&idCanal=undefined \n |accessdate=28 September 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215052223/http://ultimahora.publico.clix.pt/noticia.aspx?id=1305931 \n |archivedate=15 February 2008 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n\nThe ASFIC's (Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Sindical dos Funcion\u00e1rios de Investiga\u00e7\u00e3o Criminal da Pol\u00edcia Judici\u00e1ria) General Secretary, Carlos Garcia, declared on 10 August 2007 that the [[Trade union|union]] representing the PJ intended to take legal action against those British journalists who had accused Portuguese police officers of forging evidence. He stated that, at the beginning of the investigation, a joint working group had been created with the British police, and that they had been working in close cooperation. Thus when the Portuguese police is criticised, so too is the British police. He claimed that the number of abductions resulting in murder was a decisive factor that determined the different methods of investigation adopted by the two forces.<ref>{{Cite news\n |title      = Agentes da PJ querem processar jornalistas ingleses\n |work       = [[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]\n |date       = 18 August 2007\n |url        = http://ultimahora.publico.clix.pt/noticia.aspx?id=1301854\n |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130416152959/http://ultimahora.publico.clix.pt/noticia.aspx?id=1301854\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 16 April 2013\n |accessdate = 1 November 2007\n}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2008, the McCanns launched a [[libel]] suit against the ''[[Daily Express]]'' and its sister newspaper, the ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]'', as well as their Sunday equivalents, following the newspapers' coverage of the case. The action concerned more than 100 stories across the four newspapers, which accused the McCanns of causing Madeleine's death and then covering it up.<ref name=\"Damages due\"/> One immediate consequence of the action was that Express Newspapers pulled all references to Madeleine from its websites.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = Express titles cut back McCann coverage\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | author=Leigh Holmwood\n | date = 13 March 2008\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/mar/13/pressandpublishing.dailyexpress\n | accessdate = 17 March 2008\n}}</ref> In a settlement reached at the [[High Court of Justice]], the newspapers agreed to run a front-page apology to the McCanns on 19 March 2008, publish another apology on the front pages of the Sunday editions of 23 March and make a statement of apology at the High Court.<ref name=\"Damages due\">{{Cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7303801.stm | title=Damages due over McCann stories | publisher=BBC News Online | date=18 March 2008 | accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref>  ''Guardian'' media commentator [[Roy Greenslade]] said it was \"unprecedented\" for four major newspapers to offer front-page apologies, but also said that it was more than warranted given that the papers had committed \"a substantial libel\" that shamed the entire British press.<ref>[[Roy Greenslade|Greenslade, Roy]]. [https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2008/mar/19/expressandstarapologiesto Express and Star apologies to McCanns bring all journalism into disrepute]. [[The Guardian]], 19 March 2008.</ref>\n\nIn its apology, the ''Express'' stated that \"a number of articles in the newspaper have suggested that the couple caused the death of their missing daughter Madeleine and then covered it up. We acknowledge that there is no evidence whatsoever to support this theory and that Kate and Gerry are completely innocent of any involvement in their daughter's disappearance.\"<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://www.dailyexpress.co.uk/posts/view/38490 | title=Kate and Gerry McCann: Sorry |work=Daily Express |location=UK | date=19 March 2008 | accessdate = 19 March 2008}}</ref> The McCanns also accepted \u00a3550,000 ($1.1&nbsp;million) damages and costs.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/europe/03/19/mccann.newspapers/index.html | title=McCanns win $1M libel damages | publisher=CNN | date=19 March 2008 |accessdate = 19 March 2008}}</ref> They promised to pay the damages into ''Madeleine's Fund''.<ref name=\"Damages due\"/>\n\nRobert Murat instigated defamation proceedings against [[Sky News]] and 11 British newspapers, in April 2008. He used London solicitors Simons Muirhead & Burton on a [[Contingent fee|conditional fee]] agreement. The first paper to settle was ''[[The Scotsman]]'' who published an apology on 15 May but paid no damages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=41189&c=1 |title=Scotsman apologises to Robert Murat for defamatory Madeline McCann story |date=16 May 2008 |accessdate=18 May 2008 |author=Patrick Smith |publisher=[[Press Gazette]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080520233811/http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=41189&c=1 |archivedate=20 May 2008 }}</ref> The newspaper groups [[Associated Newspapers Ltd|Associated Newspapers]], [[Express Newspapers]], [[Trinity Mirror|MGN Limited]] and [[News International|News Group Newspapers]] settled with Murat, on 17 July, for a \u00a3600,000 payout. They also issued a public apology in the [[High Court of Justice|High Court]].<ref name=\"Robert Murat accepts \u00a3600,000\"/> [[BSkyB]] also paid him damages in a separate libel case.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/madeleinemccann/3458813/Madeleine-McCann-Robert-Murat-accepts-libel-damages-from-BSkyB.html |title=Madeleine McCann: Robert Murat accepts libel damages from BSkyB |publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London |date=14 November 2008 |accessdate=19 September 2011}}</ref> Sergey Malinka, and Murat's girlfriend, Michaela Walczuch, accepted more than \u00a3100,000 each.<ref name=\"Robert Murat accepts \u00a3600,000\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article4350087.ece |title=Robert Murat accepts \u00a3600,000 after Madeleine McCann allegations |date=17 July 2008 |accessdate=17 July 2008 |author=Nico Hines |work=The Times | location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe friends of the McCanns, known as the [[Disappearance of Madeleine McCann#Friends|Tapas Seven]], were awarded around \u00a3375,000 in damages and secured printed apologies from Express Newspapers. The friends have donated the settlement monies to the Fund. The apologies, printed in both the Daily Express and Daily Star, said \"In articles ... we suggested that the holiday companions of Kate and Gerry McCann might have covered up the true facts concerning Madeleine McCann's disappearance and/or misled the authorities investigating her disappearance. We also reported speculation that ... Dr Russell O'Brien, was suspected of involvement with Madeleine's abduction. We now accept that these suggestions should never have been made and were completely untrue. ...\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/mediatechnologyandtelecoms/media/3206334/Madeleine-McCann-Daily-Express-publishes-apology-to-Tapas-Seven.html |title=Madeleine McCann: Daily Express publishes apology to 'Tapas Seven' |date=16 October 2008 |accessdate=17 October 2008 |author=Matthew Moore  |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK }}</ref>\n\nThe McCanns applied for an injunction, on 8 December 2009, prohibiting the sale of the book, written by Gon\u00e7alo Amaral, ''Maddie, a Verdade da Mentira'' (''Maddie, the Truth of the Lie''), and launched a libel suit against Amaral.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.correiomanha.pt/noticia.aspx?contentid=9F1855F4-CDF8-493C-8478-EF3D122CEFE1&channelid=00000010-0000-0000-0000-000000000010&h=3 |title=McCann no julgamento do livro de Gon\u00e7alo Amaral |date=8 December 2009 |accessdate=8 December 2009 |publisher=[[Correio da Manh\u00e3]]}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* ''Maddie 129'', {{ISBN|978-989-8028-61-7}}, that covers the 129 days between Madeleine's disappearance and the McCanns' return to Rothley. The book claims to identify contradictions and unanswered questions in the accounts of the McCanns and their friends. It was published in early November 2007, in English by [[Prime Books]], and written by two Portuguese journalists Hern\u00e2ni Carvalho and Lu\u00eds Maia.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = Madeleine book notes the 'contradictions'\n | author=Ned Temko\n |work=The Observer |location=UK\n | date = 4 November 2007\n | url = http://books.guardian.co.uk/news/articles/0,,2205019,00.html\n | accessdate = 13 November 2007 }}</ref>\n* ''A Culpa dos McCann'' (The Guilt of the McCanns), {{ISBN|989-8014-81-4}}, was published in Portugal in December 2007. Written by Portuguese daily newspaper [[Correio da Manh\u00e3]] editor-in-chief Manuel Catarino, it was published by [[Guerra & Paz]].<ref>{{Cite news\n |title=Madeleine book notes the 'contradictions' \n |author=Alison Flood \n |work=[[Bookseller.com]] \n |date=3 December 2007 \n |url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/49158-second-mccann-book-in-portugal.html \n |accessdate=9 December 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071206224157/http://www.thebookseller.com/news/49158-second-mccann-book-in-portugal.html \n |archivedate= 6 December 2007 \n}}</ref>\n* ''Madeleine: A Heartbreaking and Extraordinary Disappearance'', {{ISBN|978-0-85079-348-2}}, was published in December 2007 by [[Daily Express|Express Newspapers]] and written by Robert Downing.\n* ''A Estrela de Madeleine'' (The Star of Madeleine), {{ISBN|978-972-23-3890-5}}, written by Paulo Pereira Crist\u00f3v\u00e3o, was published by Editorial Presen\u00e7a.<ref>{{Cite news\n |title      = Das p\u00e1ginas dos jornais para o neg\u00f3cio dos livros\n |author     = Patr\u00edcia Jesus\n |work       = [[Di\u00e1rio de Not\u00edcias]]\n |date       = 21 July 2008\n |url        = https://dn.sapo.pt/especiais/Interior.aspx?content_id=981318&especial=Caso%20Maddie&seccao=SOCIEDADE//index.html\n |accessdate = 7 June 2009\n}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* ''O Enigma da Praia da Luz'' (The Enigma of Praia da Luz), {{ISBN|978-989-8014-91-7}}, was written by Francisco Duarte de Carvalho and was published by Editora Guerra & Paz.\n* ''Maddie, a Verdade da Mentira'' (Maddie, the Truth of the Lie), {{ISBN|978-989-8174-12-3}}, written by Gon\u00e7alo Amaral, who had originally headed the police investigation, was published by Guerra & Paz on 24 July 2008. In the book, Amaral detailed his belief that Madeleine died in the family's holiday apartment.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = Detective's book claims Madeleine McCann died in apartment\n | author=Haroon Siddique\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 24 July 2008\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/jul/24/madeleinemccann.portugal\n | accessdate = 26 July 2008}}</ref>\n*''What really happened to Madeleine McCann?'' subtitled '60 reasons which suggest that she was not abducted', {{ISBN|978-0-9507954-7-8}}, was written by Tony Bennett and was published on 31 October 2008 by The Madeleine Foundation.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = Madeleine\n | date = 31 October 2008\n | id ={{ASIN|095079547X|country=it}}\n }}</ref>\n*''Madeleine'', {{ISBN|978-0-593-06791-8}}, was written by Kate McCann and was published by [[Bantam Press]] on 12 May 2011.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = What Really Happened to Madeleine McCann?: 60 Reasons Which Suggest She Was Not Abducted\n | date = 12 May 2011\n | id ={{ASIN|0593067916|country=uk}}\n }}</ref>\n\n==Film and television==\n\n===BBC Panorama===\nThe BBC ''[[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]]'' current affairs programme screened an edition called 'The Mystery of Madeleine McCann' on 19 November 2007. It attracted 5.3&nbsp;million viewers.<ref name=\"ITV documentary\">{{Cite news\n | title = McCanns mull ITV documentary offer\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | author=Leigh Holmwood\n | date = 11 March 2008\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/mar/11/madeleinemccann.itv\n | accessdate = 11 March 2008 }}</ref>\nThe programme reviewed the evidence that was currently publicly available but did not come to a conclusion on what happened to Madeleine.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = The Mystery of Madeleine McCann\n |publisher=BBC\n | date = 18 November 2007\n | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/panorama/7100536.stm\n | accessdate = 30 November 2007}}</ref>\nThe original producer of the programme walked out, claiming that criticism of the media and the Portuguese police had been toned down for the broadcast version.<ref name=\"ITV documentary\"/>\n\n===Proposed documentaries===\nThe McCanns have given permission for talks to open about the possibility of the disappearance being made into a documentary film. Spokesman [[Clarence Mitchell (journalist)|Clarence Mitchell]] confirmed that a meeting, with [[Talent agent|talent agency]] and production company [[IMG (business)|IMG]] to discuss a possible film, was held in December 2007, but the proposal was abandoned.<ref name=\"ITV documentary\"/><ref>{{Cite news\n | title = Parents may turn Madeleine McCann story into a Hollywood movie\n | author=Rajeev Syal and Dominic Kennedy\n |work=The Times |location=UK\n | date = 9 January 2008\n | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/panorama/7100536.stm\n | accessdate = 9 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nMitchell also confirmed, in March 2008, that discussions were taking place with [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] and other companies over the possibility of the McCanns appearing in a documentary, which would focus on missing children in general and the different initiatives used to help look for them.<ref name=\"ITV documentary\"/> The programme, ''Madeleine, One Year On: Campaign For Change'', was broadcast on [[ITV1]] on 30 April 2008. The programme's producers said the McCanns had no editorial control and were not paid, although \u00a310,000 was donated to the Find Madeleine Fund.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Rachel Williams|title=Madeleine anniversary: McCanns tell of regrets in TV documentary|work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/apr/30/madeleinemccann.itv|date=30 April 2008|accessdate=30 April 2008 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n===TVI documentary===\nA television documentary, ''Maddie, a Verdade da Mentira'' (''Maddie, the Truth of the Lie''), based on the book, by Gon\u00e7alo Amaral, of the same name, was produced by [[Televis\u00e3o Independente|TVI]]. It was broadcast on 13 April 2009.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.novelasnacionais.com/tvi/noticias/1761-maddie%E2%80%93a-verdade-da-mentira-na-tvi |title=\"Maddie \u2013 A Verdade da Mentira\" na TVI |date=10 April 2009 |accessdate=8 December 2009 |publisher=[[Novelas Nacionais]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714203046/http://www.novelasnacionais.com/tvi/noticias/1761-maddie%E2%80%93a-verdade-da-mentira-na-tvi |archivedate=14 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The documentary pulled in an audience of over 2&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://dn.sapo.pt/especiais/interior.aspx?content_id=1225510&especial=Caso%20Maddie&seccao=SOCIEDADE |title='A Verdade da Mentira' pela Europa |date=8 May 2009 |accessdate=8 December 2009 |publisher=[[Correio da Manh\u00e3]] }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Implications for television programmes and films==\nOn 9 May 2007, [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] announced it would be rewriting a planned child kidnap [[Plot (narrative)|plot]], despite having already filmed some scenes, from their popular soap ''[[Coronation Street]]''.<ref name=\"corrie\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6638171.stm|title=Street rethinks child kidnap plot|publisher=BBC News|date=9 May 2007|accessdate=25 May 2007}}</ref> Similarly, on 23 May, the [[BBC TV|BBC]] also announced that it was scrapping a [[Subplot|storyline]] from rival soap ''[[EastEnders]]'', that had already been filmed, which also was to feature the kidnapping of a child.{{cn|date=January 2020}} In both cases these plot lines were removed or altered due to the parallel with the Madeleine case, and because the channels did not want to cause further distress to the McCann family.<ref name=\"corrie\" />\n\n[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] was criticised, in September 2007,  over the showing of ''[[Torn (TV series)|Torn]]'', a three-part original drama series. The plot involved the disappearance of a four-year-old girl and the family's search for her. ITV responded to the criticism by stating that ''Torn'' had been written two years earlier and filmed two months before Madeleine disappeared.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Farmer|first=Ben|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1563414/ITV-criticised-over-Madeleine-McCann-drama.html|title=ITV criticised over 'Madeleine McCann' drama |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=18 September 2007|accessdate=3 August 2009 | location=London}}</ref> Also in September 2007, actor and director [[Ben Affleck]] postponed the UK release of his film ''[[Gone Baby Gone]]'', which had been scheduled for release on 28 December,\nto 18 April 2008. Its plot centres on the abduction of a four-year-old girl who is left at home alone by her mother. The actress who plays the girl, [[Madeline O'Brien]], reportedly resembles Madeleine. According to Affleck, the release of the film in Britain was delayed because those involved with the film didn't want to \"touch a nerve or inflame anybody's sensitivities.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Franklin|first=Katie|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6992601.stm|title=US film pulled over McCann case |author2=Neil Smith |publisher=BBC News|date=13 September 2007|accessdate=13 September 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Tributes==\n[[File:Tributes for Madeleine McCann, Rothley, 17 May 2007.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Tributes in [[Rothley]] on 17 May 2007]]\nChurch services were held in Portugal and the UK on 3 May 2008, to mark the first anniversary of Madeleine's disappearance.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Esther Addley|title=Services to mark year since Madeleine vanished|work=The Guardian |location=UK|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/may/03/madeleinemccann.internationalcrime|date=3 May 2008|accessdate=3 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Appeals==\nThere were many appeals for Madeleine's safe return, including from her family, celebrities, church leaders, and the police.\n\n===From the family===\nHer father, Gerry McCann, said, \"Words cannot describe the anguish and despair that we are feeling. Please, if you have Madeleine, let her come home to her Mummy, Daddy, brother and sister.\"<ref name=\"yahoo story\">{{Cite news|url=http://uk.news.yahoo.com/rtrs/20070505/tpl-uk-portugal-girl-4b8df73.html|title=Abducted girl's parents pray for her safe return|publisher=[[Reuters]]|author=Axel Bugge|date=6 May 2007|accessdate = 6 May 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070508145030/http://uk.news.yahoo.com/rtrs/20070505/tpl-uk-portugal-girl-4b8df73.html |archivedate = 8 May 2007}}</ref> He went on to say that the family would leave \"no stone unturned\" in the search for Madeleine and that he and his wife \"remained positive.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6645341.stm|title=Madeleine parents 'won't give up'|publisher=BBC News|date=11 May 2007|accessdate = 11 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nMadeleine's aunt, Philomena McCann, drew up a poster<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www1.sky.com/news/Madeleine.pdf |title=Copy of 'Missing Madeleine' poster |publisher=[[Sky News]] |accessdate=9 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612042338/http://www1.sky.com/news/Madeleine.pdf |archivedate=12 June 2007 }}</ref> to circulate in a chain email to help find the child. She also commented during a live phone interview that there was little coverage of the case in other countries apart from the UK and Portugal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,91210-1264740,00.html |title=Madeleine's Family Send Out Email Poster |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=9 May 2007 |accessdate=9 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070512095111/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0%2C%2C91210-1264740%2C00.html |archivedate=12 May 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===From the police===\nOn 21 May 2007, the British [[Child Exploitation and Online Protection Centre]] (CEOP) reported that British police are calling on visitors to the Ocean Club Resort, Praia da Luz, or the surrounding areas in the two weeks leading up to Madeleine's disappearance on Thursday 3 May to provide copies of any relevant photographs taken during their stay, in an attempt to identify an abductor using a [[Biometrics|biometric]] [[Facial recognition system|facial recognition application]], through which the features of bystanders in those photographs could be compared to those of international sex offenders and other criminals.<ref name=photographs>{{Cite news|url=http://www.madeleine.ceopupload.com/|title=Help find Madeleine McCann|publisher=[[Child Exploitation and Online Protection Centre]]|date=21 May 2007|accessdate=21 May 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070523075031/http://madeleine.ceopupload.com/|archivedate=23 May 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-1266780,00.html |title=Madeleine's Dad Arrives Back In Portugal |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=22 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070615052316/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0%2C%2C30100-1266780%2C00.html |archivedate=15 June 2007 }}</ref> By 1 June, over one thousand photographs had been uploaded.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/932ba02b5ba8922f8de6dfd1e0f97529.html |title=Madeleine McCann: Photos flood in |publisher=[[ITV News]] |date=1 June 2007 |accessdate=2 June 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929090400/http://www.itv.com/news/932ba02b5ba8922f8de6dfd1e0f97529.html |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===From religious leaders===\nOn 11 May 2007 Roman Catholic [[Archbishop]] [[Mario Joseph Conti|Mario Conti]] of [[Glasgow]] said that his prayers would continue for the safe return of Madeleine<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.christiantoday.com/article/1m.reward.offered.for.missing.madeleine/10740.htm|title=\u00a31m Reward Offered for Missing Madeleine|publisher=[[Christian Today]]|date=11 May 2007|accessdate = 2 June 2007}}</ref> Then on 30 May, [[Pope Benedict XVI]], at an audience in the [[Apostolic Palace|Vatican]] with the McCanns, promised to pray for the girl's safe return.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/pope/story/0,,2091210,00.html|title=Madeleine's parents meet Pope|work=The Guardian |location=UK|date=30 May 2007|accessdate = 30 May 2007|first=Peter | last=Walker}}</ref>\n\n===From sport===\n\n====From football====\n[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] footballer [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], who is Portuguese, made a televised appeal on [[Manchester United TV|MUTV]] for her safe return saying \"I was very upset to hear of the abduction of Madeleine McCann and I appeal to anyone with information to come forward - please come forward.\"<ref name=portugalbbc /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/breaking/story.asp?j=14248132&p=y4z48y78&n=14248220&x=|title=Star Ronaldo in Madeleine appeal|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|date=8 May 2007|accessdate = 9 May 2007}}</ref> [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and [[England national football team|England]] footballer [[John Terry]] and his Portuguese teammate [[Paulo Ferreira]] said that they were \"devastated to hear that young Maddy was abducted. Our thoughts and feelings go out to her parents, her family and we are urging anyone out there with any information at all, please, please, please come forward.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/index_0456c056818c3d70b8184f9f88a1701e.html |title=Paedophile link probed in Madeleine hunt |publisher=[[ITV News]] |date=9 May 2007 |accessdate=9 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929121942/http://www.itv.com/news/index_0456c056818c3d70b8184f9f88a1701e.html |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref> On 11 May 2007, [[David Beckham]] also made a public appeal. \"If you have seen this little girl please could you go to your local authorities or police and give any information that you have,\" said Beckham, holding up a poster with a photograph of Madeleine.<ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/05/11/europe/EU-GEN-Spain-Beckham-Appeal.php \"David Beckham appeals for information on missing toddler Madeleine McCann\"], ''[[International Herald Tribune]]'', 11 May 2007</ref>\n\nAfter a picture was released of Madeleine in an [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] shirt, Everton's Portuguese footballers [[Nuno Valente]] and [[Manuel Henriques Tavares Fernandes|Manuel Fernandes]] appealed for any news on her whereabouts and [[Phil Neville]] issued the following statement on behalf of the club. \"Everton has fans all over the world and I know that they, along with everyone connected with the football club, are hoping and praying for Madeleine's safe return. Our thoughts are very much with the family at this extremely distressing time.\" Manager [[David Moyes]] added \"Everybody here is desperately wanting to hear good news and my thoughts and prayers are with the family. If anybody out there knows anything, please come forward\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/statement-for-madeleine.html|title=Everton appeal for Madeleine|publisher=[[Everton F.C.]]|date=11 May 2007|accessdate=11 May 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070512083826/http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/statement-for-madeleine.html|archive-date=12 May 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] footballer [[Neil Lennon]] made an appeal for Madeleine's safety, and yellow armbands were worn on 12 May 2007 against [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] to mark her fourth birthday.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/stories/news_110507090633.aspx |title=Celtic players to wear yellow armbands |publisher=[[Celtic F.C.]] |date=11 May 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513024027/http://www.celticfc.net/news/stories/news_110507090633.aspx |archivedate=13 May 2007 }}</ref>\n\nA video appealing for help with the search for Madeleine was broadcast to Spanish football fans visiting the city of [[Glasgow]] for the [[2007 UEFA Cup Final]] on 16 May.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/6664081.stm|title=Spanish fans shown Madeleine film|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|date=16 May 2007|accessdate = 19 May 2007}}</ref> Another film was aired at half-time during the English [[FA Cup]] Final on 19 May.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,91210-1266418,00.html |title=Candle-Lit Vigil And Prayers For Madeleine |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=18 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070604081748/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0%2C%2C91210-1266418%2C00.html |archivedate= 4 June 2007 }}</ref> Before their departure for the [[2007 UEFA Champions League Final]] on Monday 21 May, [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]'s squad were photographed with a banner appealing for any information on Madeleine's whereabouts.<ref name=\"silence\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6677037.stm|title=Minute silence held for Madeleine|publisher=BBC News|date=21 May 2007|accessdate=21 May 2007}}</ref>\n\n====From cricket====\nThe [[England cricket team]] wore yellow ribbons during the [[Lord's Cricket Ground|Lords']] [[Test cricket|Test match]] against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]], in May 2007, to show their support for Madeleine. A picture of Madeleine was also shown on the big screen at the match.<ref>{{Cite news | title = England cricket team join support to help find Madeleine |work=Daily Mail |location=UK | date = 25 May 2007 | url = http://www.mailonsunday.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/news.html?in_article_id=457713&in_page_id=1770 | accessdate = 26 May 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===From education===\nTo further publicise Madeleine's disappearance, the [[Student|pupils]] of [[Bishop Ellis Catholic Primary School]], the school that she would have attended from September 2007, lined up in the school's [[playground]] on 18 June to spell out ''Find Madeleine''. This was easily readable from the air.{{cn|date=January 2020}} In August the school announced that they had saved a desk, coat peg and locker for the child.<ref>{{Cite news | title = A peg for Maddy | work = The Daily Mirror | location = UK | date = 19 August 2007 | url = https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/topstories/2007/08/18/a-peg-for-maddy-89520-19655192/ | accessdate = 28 August 2007 }}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | title = Empty seat for Maddie on first day at school | work = Daily Express | location = UK | date = 31 August 2007 | url = http://www2.dailyexpress.co.uk/posts/view/17756/Madeleine's-school-seat-left-empty | archive-url = https://archive.is/20070928134705/http://www2.dailyexpress.co.uk/posts/view/17756/Madeleine's-school-seat-left-empty | url-status = dead | archive-date = 28 September 2007 | accessdate = 31 August 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n\n===Of the public and political reaction===\nThe scale of the public reaction provoked negative comment from a number of media commentators. On 16 May 2007 on [[BBC Radio 4]], [[Matthew Parris]] said that politicians' displays of concern were \"hollow\". He also claimed that politicians \"read the common newspapers and they decide this is what the common people feel, and they get all caught up with it. But it's all to do with trying to associate themselves with the common herd and they're not part of it. They're politicians\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/index.php?menuID=1&subID=1407 |title=There's something hollow about it |author=Matthew Parris |work=[[The First Post]] |date=16 May 2007 |accessdate=31 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070523055235/http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/index.php?menuID=1&subID=1407 |archivedate=23 May 2007 |author-link=Matthew Parris }}</ref> He went on to say, in his column on 17 May, that [[Member of Parliament|MPs]] wearing yellow ribbons was mawkish and an attempt to \"tap in to the emotions of the mob\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/matthew_parris/article1801174.ece|title=Now no one will realise that I'm nuts about Hazel|author=Matthew Parris|work=The Times |location=UK|date=17 May 2007|accessdate = 19 May 2007 |author-link=Matthew Parris}}</ref> Then on 19 May, ''[[The Guardian]]'' described the public reaction as hysteria and drew a parallel with the response to the ''[[News of the World]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Pedophilia|anti-paedophile]] campaign.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Emma |last=Brockes |authorlink=Emma Brockes |author=|title=In chatrooms and message boards, Madeleine hysteria grips the world |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk_news/story/0,,2083248,00.html |work=The Guardian |location=UK |id= |pages= |page= |date=19 May 2007|accessdate=19 May 2007 |language= }}</ref>\n\nWriting in [[The Times]] on 16 September, [[India Knight]] criticised the on-line community for its censorious attitude and its willingness to rush to judgement whilst pointing out that the McCanns had contributed to the public's obsession with the case by their extensive and well-orchestrated media campaign.<ref>{{Cite news |author=India Knight |title=Madeleine McCann: You are all guilty |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article2459924.ece |work=The Times |location=UK |date=16 September 2007 |accessdate=6 December 2007 |author-link=India Knight }}</ref> A debate on the disappearance was held at the [[London School of Economics]] on 30 January 2008. Although the debate was inconclusive, the stridently critical attitude of the on-line community towards the McCanns, noted by Knight, also manifested itself in the audience reaction.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Roy Greenslade |title=The McCanns' debate: from banality to an outpouring of bile |url=http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/greenslade/2008/01/the_mccanns_debate_from_banali.html |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=31 January 2008 |accessdate=1 February 2008 |author-link=Roy Greenslade }}</ref>\n\n===Of the media coverage===\n\n====Importance of the coverage====\nSome have suggested that the high level of media coverage could be [[Missing white woman syndrome|attributable to Madeleine's race, nationality, or socio-economic status]].<!-- According to [[UNICEF]] (the UN children's fund), 1.2&nbsp;million children are trafficked every year around the world. --> ''[[The Independent]]'', in an editorial on 15 May 2007, described the media coverage as showing a warped sense of priorities and condemned the criticism of the Portuguese authorities as [[jingoism]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://comment.independent.co.uk/leading_articles/article2542346.ece|title=Wild theories and a warped sense of priorities|author=Editorial|work=The Independent|date=15 May 2007|accessdate=19 May 2007|location=London|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070517042757/http://comment.independent.co.uk/leading_articles/article2542346.ece|archivedate=17 May 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In his 17 May column in Portugal's ''[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]'' newspaper, the former head of Portugal's bar association, Jos\u00e9 Miguel J\u00fadice, said the enormous mobilisation was because the little girl \"is English, white, and the daughter of doctors.\"<ref name=IPS>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=37797 |title=Some Missing Children More Equal than Others |author=Mario de Queiroz |publisher=[[Inter Press Service]] |date=18 May 2007 |accessdate=19 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070613144404/http://www.ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=37797 |archivedate=13 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May, ''[[Inter Press Service]]'' drew attention to the fact that some observers point out that Madeleine comes from a well-heeled British family (both of her parents are doctors), unlike so many Portuguese or immigrant children whose disappearance has drawn scant attention from the press.<ref name=IPS/> There has also been criticism of the weight put on this case in the light of many other, unpublicised, children's disappearances.<ref name=\"IPS\"/>\n\nAlso on 18 May, ''[[The Scotsman]]'' commented that \"... there was evidence that public opinion, while strongly supportive of the child's distraught parents Kate and Gerry McCann, was growing alarmed at what it viewed as relentless, almost prurient coverage.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Baker |first=Luke |title=Has Britain gone overboard for missing Madeleine? |work=The Scotsman |location=UK |date=18 May 2007 |url=http://news.scotsman.com/latest.cfm?id=776102007 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120731022402/http://news.scotsman.com/latest.cfm?id=776102007 |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 July 2012 |accessdate=23 May 2007 }}</ref> [[Channel 4 News]] presenter [[Alex Thomson (journalist)|Alex Thomson]] has said the Madeleine McCann story did not deserve its news ranking. \"I've been sickened by the way the media have allowed themselves to be taken for a full-scale ride by the McCanns.\" He added that the parents' conduct, \"a contributory factor in the abduction, was largely downplayed or ignored altogether by sycophantic, gullible blanket coverage.\"<ref>{{Cite news\n |last=Thomson \n |first=Alex \n |title=Paris Hilton? Not on my watch! \n |work=[[Press Gazette]] \n |date=6 July 2007 \n |url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=6&storycode=38152&c=1 \n |accessdate=6 July 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070709114545/http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=6&storycode=38152&c=1 \n |archivedate= 9 July 2007 \n}}</ref>\n\nRaymond Snoddy wrote in ''Marketing'': \"To what extent has all this coverage been kept afloat for so long because the child is white and photogenic, and has articulate, resourceful parents? Of course, the news value of the story was also enhanced by context - everyone's worst nightmare, a child snatched from an apparently secure apartment in an upmarket holiday resort. But the sad truth is that if a black child had been snatched from a [[sink estate]] in Liverpool or Glasgow, the chances are you would not know their name.\"<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Snoddy\n | first = Raymond\n | title = Was TV coverage right for Madeleine?\n |work=Marketing\n | date = 13 June 2007\n | page = 20\n | id = {{ProQuest|214980219}}\n }}</ref>\n\nGerry, who had encouraged media coverage, criticised ''[[De Telegraaf]]'' on 14 June for publishing a letter<ref name=\"BBCletter\">{{Cite news | title = Madeleine police probing letter |publisher=BBC News | date = 13 June 2007 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6749131.stm | accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref> claiming to know the [[Disappearance of Madeleine McCann#Other lines of enquiry|location of Madeleine's body]], calling it \"an irresponsible piece of journalism\" and \"insensitive and cruel\".<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Siddique\n | first = Haroon\n | title = Madeleine's parents condemn publication of letter\n |work=The Guardian\n | date = 14 June 2007\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/crime/article/0,,2103138,00.html?gusrc=rss&feed=11\n | accessdate = 14 June 2007\n| location=London}}</ref> Portuguese police searched the site but found no trace of Madeleine.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Reis\n | first = Paolo\n | title = Detectives' hunt for Madeleine 'was illegal'\n |work=The Times |location=UK\n | date = 25 August 2007\n | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article2324229.ece\n | accessdate = 1 September 2007}}</ref> At the [[Edinburgh International Television Festival]] on 25 August, Gerry complained about the amount of media attention, on the disappearance, that he claimed was 10 times what he had expected. He also criticised wild speculation being erroneously reported as fact.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Kelbie\n | first = Paul\n | title = Madeleine's father appeals for restraint by the media\n |work=The Observer |location=UK\n | date = 26 August 2007\n | url = http://observer.guardian.co.uk/uk_news/story/0,,2156496,00.html\n | accessdate = 26 August 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThere was criticism by the ''[[Daily Express]]'' of the stories run in the Portuguese media. In an article on 28 August that summarised the speculation, the ''Daily Express'' accused the local media of \"a vile whispering campaign, which has led to them [the McCanns] suffering a daily torrent of smears\" and described the stories suggesting that the McCanns had involvement in their daughter's disappearance as \"lies\".<ref>{{Cite news\n |last        = Flanagan\n |first       = Padraic\n |title       = McCanns Rocked By Stream Of Vicious Smears\n |work        = Daily Express\n |location    = UK\n |date        = 28 August 2007\n |url         = http://www2.dailyexpress.co.uk/posts/view/17504/McCanns-rocked-by-stream-of-vicious-smears\n |accessdate  = 29 August 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://archive.is/20070928134727/http://www2.dailyexpress.co.uk/posts/view/17504/McCanns-rocked-by-stream-of-vicious-smears\n |archivedate = 28 September 2007\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nJournalist [[Martin Bell]] accused the [[BBC]] of wasting hundreds of thousands of pounds of taxpayers' money in its coverage of the disappearance. In January 2008 Bell said \"I'm calling it the death of news. It is the stupidification of the news agenda. It is pretty obvious television news has lost its way not just with the McCann case but that has been extreme.\"<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Nicole\n | first = Martin\n | title = BBC 'wasted money' covering McCann case\n |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK\n | date = 16 January 2008\n | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2008/01/16/nbbc116.xml\n | accessdate = 16 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\nA comparison was drawn, in early March 2008, between the publicity given to Madeleine with the much lower key publicity for the [[disappearance of Shannon Matthews]]. [[The Guardian]] explained this by stating that \"Overarching everything is social class\" but they added that Shannon going missing in the UK made a difference. [[The Independent]] took the same line saying \"Kate and Gerry McCann had a lot: they were a couple of nice middle-class doctors on holiday in an upmarket resort\" \"Karen Matthews is not as elegant, nor as eloquent\".<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Greenslade\n | first = Roy\n | title = Why is missing Shannon not getting the same coverage as Madeleine?\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 5 March 2008\n | url = http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/greenslade/2008/03/why_is_missing_shannon_not_get.html\n | accessdate = 5 March 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Nicole\n | first = Martin\n | title = Missing: The contrasting searches for Shannon and Madeleine\n |work=The Independent |location=UK\n | date = 2 March 2008\n | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/missing-the-contrasting-searches-for-shannon-and-madeleine-790207.html\n | accessdate = 5 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn his book [[Spoilt Rotten: The Toxic Cult of Sentimentality|''Spoilt Rotten'']] [[Theodore Dalrymple]] analyses critically the media attention and reaction to the disappearance, and specifically how certain elements in the media interpreted the lack of emotion displayed by the girl's parents as evidence of guilt.<ref>{{Cite book\n  |ref=harv\n  |last= Dalrymple\n  |first= Theodore\n  |title=Spoilt Rotten: The Toxic Cult of Sentimentality\n  |publisher=Gibson Square Books Ltd\n  |year=2010\n  |isbn=978-1-906142-61-2\n  |page=138|title-link= Spoilt Rotten: The Toxic Cult of Sentimentality\n }}</ref>\n\n====Objectivity of the coverage====\nIn an interview published on 1 July [[Martin Brunt]], a [[Sky News]] journalist who had covered the case extensively, conceded that the media's handling of the Madeleine McCann disappearance had been flawed. \"It's the view of a few of us that when we look back over the first two or three weeks of the coverage we were in some ways over-sympathetic. We kind of adopted the tone and the language that the family did. I think we perhaps lost our objectivity a bit, we became a bit too subjective about the story.\"<ref>{{Cite news\n |last        = Brunt\n |first       = Martin\n |title       = Brunt of the Yard presents his case\n |work        = The Independent\n |location    = UK\n |date        = 2 July 2007\n |url         = http://news.independent.co.uk/media/article2725892.ece\n |accessdate  = 2 July 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070706231113/http://news.independent.co.uk/media/article2725892.ece\n |archivedate = 6 July 2007\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nThe British media has been criticised for being heavily critical of the Portuguese police and legal system.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Jenkins\n | first = Simon\n | title = The British media does not do responsibility. It does stories\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 18 May 2007\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/story/0,,2082507,00.html\n | accessdate = 10 September 2007 }}</ref> ''The Guardian'' noted that the British media compared the Portuguese procedures with British procedures unfavourably and unfairly.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Berlins\n | first = Marcel\n | title = Media have rushed to judge Portuguese police\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 10 September 2007\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/law/story/0,,2165920,00.html\n | accessdate = 10 September 2007 }}</ref>\nLikewise, ''[[The Times]]'' published an editorial titled \"Exactly how guilty are the Portuguese police?\" and stated that there had been a rush to judge the Portuguese authorities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hume |first=Mick |title=Exactly how guilty are the Portuguese police? |work=The Times |location=UK |date=11 September 2007 |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/mick_hume/article2426174.ece |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505100731/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/mick_hume/article2426174.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 May 2013 |accessdate=11 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\nMatthew Parris, writing for ''The Times'' in August, chastised the British and Portuguese media for what he described as \"assassination-by-innuendo\" of suspect Robert Murat, who those involved closely in the case believed was innocent. \"For the rest of the world, however, glancing in passing at headlines and skimming news reports over its coffee, the name Murat is now synonymous with 'creepy oddball and obvious suspect',\" Parris wrote. He concluded, \"The whole disgusting business, the whole media-driven infatuation with this little girl and her parents, the whole sick, morbid, sentimental campaign of news generation and news manipulation, has been a disgrace to the British media.\"<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Parris\n | first = Matthew\n | authorlink = Matthew Parris\n | title = The forgotten victim in the McCann case\n |work=The Times |location=UK\n | date = 25 August 2007\n | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/matthew_parris/article2324200.ece\n | accessdate = 11 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Horrocks]], the head of [[BBC]] TV News, denied claims in September 2007 that the BBC was biased in favour of the McCanns. Some viewers had suggested that the McCanns had been treated in an overly positive light because they were white, middle class doctors.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Borland\n | first = Sophie\n | title = BBC: We are 'not biased' towards Madeleine McCann parents\n |work=The Daily Telegraph\n | date = 12 September 2007\n | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/09/12/nmaddy412.xml\n | accessdate = 12 September 2007\n| location=London}}</ref> Then Horrocks criticised rival [[Broadcasting|broadcasters]], saying \"I know that many other TV and radio networks have been absolutely extraordinary, always talking about it in terms of sympathy and their [McCanns] feelings.\"<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Plunkett\n | first = John\n | title =Horrocks warns on biased McCann reports\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 11 September 2007\n | url = http://media.guardian.co.uk/broadcast/story/0,,2166699,00.html?gusrc=rss&feed=4\n | accessdate = 11 September 2007 }}</ref> Writing in [[The Guardian]], also in September, [[Marcel Berlins]] said that the investigation had generated a wave of negative comments in the UK media towards Portuguese society, and the authorities investigating the case, as the result of ignorance of the [[Portuguese legal system]]. Berlins called it \"a touch of arrogant xenophobia\".<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Berlins\n | first = Marcel\n | title = Media have rushed to judge Portuguese police\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 10 September 2007\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/law/story/0,,2165920,00.html\n | accessdate = 27 November 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Of the publicity===\nIn early July 2007, parents criticised a cinema [[advertising|advertisement]] about the disappearance of Madeleine which showed a still picture of the girl with the statement that she had been \"snatched\" from her room. The advertisement was being screened across Britain before the children's film ''[[Shrek the Third]]'', and parents were complaining to the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]] that it might scare young children and that it detracted from parents' ability to decide how much to tell their children.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Bennett\n | first = Rosemary\n | title = Mothers protest over Madeleine advert before showings of Shrek\n |work=The Times\n | date = 3 July 2007\n | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article2017815.ece\n | accessdate = 3 July 2007\n| location=London}}</ref> Following the protests, the advertisements were quickly withdrawn.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Lane\n | first = Harriet\n | title = The power of mums\n |work=The Times |location=UK\n | date = 5 July 2007\n | url = http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/families/article2026302.ece\n | accessdate = 5 July 2007 }}</ref> Subsequently, however, the advertisement, which had received a [[British Board of Film Classification]] to be aired in U-certificate films, was cleared by the Advertising Standards Authority.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Sweney\n | first = Mark\n | title = Madeleine cinema ad cleared\n |work=The Guardian |location=UK\n | date = 22 August 2007\n | url = http://media.guardian.co.uk/advertising/story/0,,2153412,00.html\n | accessdate = 24 August 2007 }}</ref>\n\nA plan to include [[bookmark]]s bearing Madeleine's image in copies of ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows]]'' was shelved. After reflection, the [[Publishing|publishers]] decided it would not be responsible to expose younger readers to the story of Madeleine's disappearance.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title = Harry Potter used in worldwide appeal to help find missing Madeleine\n |work=Daily Mail |location=UK\n | date = 17 July 2007\n | url = http://www.mailonsunday.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/news.html?in_article_id=468931&in_page_id=1770\n | accessdate = 18 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nWhilst the public response has largely been in support of the Find Maddie campaign, there have been instances where it has been criticised for drawing attention away from other missing children.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = O'Hanlon\n | first = Ellis\n | title = Sorry to bore you, but Maddy is still missing\n | publisher=The Irish Independent\n | date = 3 June 2007\n | url = http://www.independent.ie/unsorted/features/sorry-to-bore-you-but-maddy-is-still-missing-690670.html\n | accessdate = 9 September 2007}}</ref> Mark Lawson, writing in [[The Guardian]] on 26 October, criticised the McCanns for employing their own [[Spin (public relations)|spin doctor]], describing their use of what he termed \"political methods\" as a \"terrible error\".<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Lawson\n | first = Mark\n | title = Spin is not the answer\n |work=The Guardian | date = 26 October 2007\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/comment/story/0,,2199439,00.html\n | accessdate = 27 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nCarlos Anjos, president of the ''Association of Criminal Investigation Staff'', criticised the McCanns, on 6 November, for creating a \"monster of information\" that hindered the investigation. He also stated that they should not have publicised the [[coloboma]] in her right eye which he claimed put the life of the girl at risk.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Brown\n | first = David\n | title = Kate and Gerry McCann 'created information monster' that hindered search for Madeleine McCann\n | work=The Times\n | date = 6 November 2007\n | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article2820330.ece\n | accessdate = 7 November 2007 }}</ref> This was echoed by Fernando Jos\u00e9 Pinto Monteiro, the [[Attorney General]], who said that, if she had been abducted, the worldwide campaign would have turned Madeleine into a liability and that it was likely that her abductor had already killed her.<ref>{{Cite news\n | last = Govan\n | first = Fiona\n | title = Madeleine McCann is probably dead\n | publisher=The Daily Telegraph\n | date = 23 November 2007\n | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/11/23/wmaddy123.xml\n | accessdate = 24 November 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Rewards==\nRewards offered totalled over \u00a32.6&nbsp;million including:\n* [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1,500,000 ([[Euro|\u20ac]]2,200,000) including [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]250,000 by the ''[[News of the World]]'', [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]250,000 by [[Sir Philip Green]], [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]50,000 by [[Simon Cowell]] and [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]25,000 by [[Coleen McLoughlin]]. Other contributors include [[Sir Richard Branson]], [[JK Rowling]], and [[Bill Kenwright]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6649951.stm|title=Madeleine reward rises to \u00a32.5m|publisher=BBC|date=12 May 2007|accessdate = 12 May 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,91210-1265397,00.html |title=Rewards For Madeleine Info Top \u00a32.5m |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=12 May 2007 |accessdate=12 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070515162520/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0%2C%2C91210-1265397%2C00.html |archivedate=15 May 2007 }}</ref>\n* [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1,000,000 (\u20ac1,470,000) by British businessman [[Stephen Winyard]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/6642115.stm|title=\u00a31m reward over missing Madeleine|publisher=BBC News|date=11 May 2007|accessdate = 11 May 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/news/article.html?in_article_id=48582&in_page_id=34|title=\u00a31m reward in hunt for Maddie|publisher=[[Metro (Associated Metro Limited)|The Metro]]|date=10 May 2007|accessdate = 10 May 2007}}</ref>\n* [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]100,000 (\u20ac147,000) by a colleague of Kate McCann.<ref name=\"Sky story\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-1264342,00.html |title=Continue To Pray For Madeleine |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=6 May 2007 |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070508050600/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0%2C%2C30100-1264342%2C00.html |archivedate= 8 May 2007 }}</ref>\n* [[Euro|\u20ac]]15,000 (\u00a310,250) by Portuguese newspaper ''[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.record.pt/noticia.asp?id=744701&idCanal=127 |title=Record oferece 15.000 euros |work=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]] |date=12 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929122204/http://www.record.pt/noticia.asp?id=744701&idCanal=127 |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"cnubarrister\">{{cite news |date=2014-11-14 |title=Shrimpton: Barrister claims missing Maddie held on boat |url=http://courtnewsuk.co.uk/shrimpton-barrister-claims-missing-maddie-held-on-boat/ |author=<!-- Staff writers; no byline --> |newspaper=Court News UK |accessdate=2016-09-24}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"cnubomb\">{{cite news |date=2014-11-19 |title=Shrimpton: Bomb scare barrister says: 'I'm not a nutter' |url=http://courtnewsuk.co.uk/shrimptonbomb-scare-barrister-says-im-not-a-nutter/ |author=<!-- Staff writers; no byline --> |newspaper=Court News UK |accessdate=2016-09-24}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"nazi\">{{cite news |author=<!-- Staff writers; no byline --> |newspaper=[[The Scotsman]] |title=Barrister jailed for Nazi Olympics bomb hoax call |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/uk/barrister-jailed-for-nazi-olympics-bomb-hoax-call-1-3682715 |date=2015-02-06 |accessdate=2016-09-19}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n\n[[Category:Disappearance of Madeleine McCann]]\n[[Category:International responses to media-related events|McCann, Madeleine]]\n", "name_user": "Conquistador2k6", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eImplications for television programmes and films:citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reactions_to_the_disappearance_of_Madeleine_McCann"}
{"title_page": "Twelve Tables", "text_new": "{{short description|Roman statute forming the law}}\n{{Roman government}}\n\nThe '''''Law of the Twelve Tables''''' ({{lang-la|Leges Duodecim Tabularum}} or ''Duodecim Tabulae'') was the legislation that stood at the foundation of [[Roman law]]. The Tables consolidated earlier traditions into an enduring set of laws.<ref>Jolowicz, H.F. ''Historical Introduction to the Study of Roman Law'' (Cambridge, 1952), 108</ref><ref name=\"Crawford\">Crawford, M.H. 'Twelve Tables' in Simon Hornblower, Antony Spawforth, and Esther Eidinow (eds.) ''Oxford Classical Dictionary'' (4th ed.)</ref>\n\nDisplayed in the [[Forum (Roman)|Forum]], \"The Twelve Tables\" stated the rights and duties of the [[Roman citizen]].  Their formulation was the result of considerable agitation by the [[plebeian]] class, who had hitherto been excluded from the higher benefits of the [[Republic]].  The law had previously been unwritten and exclusively interpreted by upper-class priests, the [[pontifices]].  Something of the regard with which later Romans came to view the Twelve Tables is captured in the remark of [[Cicero]] (106\u201343 BC) that the \"Twelve Tables...seems to me, assuredly to surpass the libraries of all the philosophers, both in weight of authority, and in plenitude of utility\".  Cicero scarcely exaggerated; the Twelve Tables formed the basis of Roman law for a thousand years.<ref>Book: \"[[The Age of Classical Civilization]]\"; Chapter \"The Twelve Tables c. 450 BC\"; p. 27</ref>\n\nThe Twelve Tables are sufficiently comprehensive that their substance has been described as a 'code',<ref>Mommsen, T. ''The History of Rome'' trans. W.P. Dickson (London,\n1864) 290</ref> although modern scholars consider this characterization exaggerated.<ref name=\"Crawford\"/> The Tables were a sequence of definitions of various private rights and procedures. They generally took for granted such things as the institutions of the family and various rituals for formal transactions. The provisions were often highly specific and diverse.<ref>Steinberg, S. 'The Twelve Tables and Their Origins: An Eighteenth-Century Debate' ''Journal of the History of Ideas'' Vol. 43, No. 3 (1982) 379\u2013396, 381</ref>\n\n==Drafting and development==\nThe Twelve Tables of Roman society were said by the Romans to have come about as a result of the long social struggle between patricians and plebeians. After the expulsion of the last king of Rome, [[Lucius Tarquinius Superbus|Tarquinius Superbus]], the [[Roman Republic|Republic]] was governed by a hierarchy of [[Roman Magistrate|magistrates]]. Initially, only [[patrician (ancient Rome)|patricians]] were eligible to become magistrates and this, among other plebeian complaints, was a source of discontent for [[plebeians]]. In the context of this unequal status, plebeians would take action to secure concessions for themselves using the threat of secession. They would threaten to leave the city with the consequence that it would grind to a halt, as the plebeians were Rome's labor force. Tradition held that one of the most important concessions won in this class struggle was the establishment of the ''Twelve Tables'', establishing basic procedural rights for all Roman citizens in relation to each other.<ref name=\"du Plessis 5-6; 29-30\">{{cite book|last=du Plessis|first=Paul|title=Borkowski's Textbook on Roman Law|year=2010|publisher=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-957488-9|pages=5\u20136, 29\u201330|edition=4th}}</ref> The drafting of the Twelve Tables may have been fomented by a desire for self-regulation by the patricians, or for other reasons.<ref name=\"Crawford\"/>\n\nAround 450 BC, the first ''[[decemviri]]'' (decemvirate, board of \"Ten Men\") were appointed to draw up the first ten tables. According to [[Titus Livius|Livy]], they sent an embassy to [[Greece]] to study the legislative system of [[Athens]], known as the [[Solonian Constitution]], but also to find out about the legislation of other [[Greeks|Greek]] cities.<ref>Livy, 2002, p. 23</ref><ref>Durant, 1942, p. 23</ref> Some scholars deny that the Romans imitated the Greeks in this respect<ref>Steinberg, S. 'The Twelve Tables and Their Origins: An Eighteenth-Century Debate' ''Journal of the History of Ideas'' Vol. 43, No. 3 (1982) 379\u2013396</ref> or suggest that they visited only the Greek cities of [[Magna Graecia|Southern Italy]], and did not travel all the way to Greece.<ref name=\"Grant 75\">{{cite book|last=Grant|first=Michael|title=History of Rome|year=1978|publisher=Prentice Hall|isbn=0-02-345610-8|pages=75|edition=1st}}</ref> In 450 BC, the second ''decemviri'' started to work on the last two tables.\n\nThe first decemvirate completed the first ten codes in 450 BC. Here is how [[Livy]] describes their creation:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"...every citizen should quietly consider each point, then talk it over with his friends, and, finally, bring forward for public discussion any additions or subtractions which seemed desirable.\" (cf. Liv. [[s:From the Founding of the City/Book 3#34|III.34]])\n</blockquote>\n\nIn 449 BC, the second decemvirate completed the last two codes, and after a ''[[secessio plebis]]'' to force the Senate to consider them, the Law of the Twelve Tables was formally promulgated.<ref>McCarty,  Nick \"Rome The Greatest Empire of the Ancient World\", The Rosen Publishing Group, 2008</ref>  According to Livy (AUC [[s:From the Founding of the City/Book 3#57|3.57.10]]) the Twelve Tables were inscribed on [[bronze]] (Pomponius (Dig. 1 tit. 2 s2 \u00a74) alone says on ivory), and posted publicly, so all Romans could read and know them.\n\nSome of the provisions are procedural to ensure fairness among all Romans in the courts, while other established legal terms dictating the legality of capital crimes, intentional homicide, treason, perjury, judicial corruption, and writing slanderous poems.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Romans valued keeping peace in the city and the Twelve Tables were a mechanism of establishing and continuing peace and equality.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Laws of the Twelve Tables ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Table 1\n|Procedure: for courts and trials\n|-\n|Table 2\n|Trials continued & Theft\n|-\n|Table 3\n|Debt\n|-\n|Table 4\n|Rights of fathers (''pater familias'') over the family\n|-\n|Table 5\n|Legal guardianship and inheritance laws\n|-\n|Table 6\n|Acquisition and possession\n|-\n|Table 7\n|Land rights & crimes\n|-\n|Table 8\n|Torts and delicts (Laws of injury)\n|-\n|Table 9\n|Public law\n|-\n|Table 10\n|Sacred law\n|-\n|Table 11\n|Supplement I\n|-\n|Table 12\n|Supplement II\n|}\n\n=== Table III: Debt ===\nThe [[laws]] the Twelve Tables covered were a way to publicly display rights that each citizen had in the public and private sphere.  These Twelve Tables displayed what was previously understood in Roman society as the unwritten laws.  The public display of the copper tablets allowed for a more balanced society between the Roman [[Patrician (ancient Rome)|patricians]] who were educated and understood the laws of legal transactions, and the Roman [[Plebeian (ancient Rome)|plebeians]] who had little education or experience in understanding law.  By revealing the unwritten rules of society to the public, the Twelve Tables provided a means of safeguard for Plebeians allowing them the opportunity to avoid financial exploitation and added balance to the [[Roman economy]]\n\nFeatured within the Twelve Tables are five rules about how to handle debtors and creditors. These rules show how the ancient Romans maintained peace with financial policy.  In his article ''Development of the Roman Law of Debt Security,'' Donald E. Phillipson states the Twelve Tables were, \u201cA set of statutes known as the Twelve Tables that was passed by an early assembly served as the foundation of the Roman private law.  The Twelve Tables were enacted in the mid-fifth century B.C. as the result of a conflict among social classes in ancient Rome.\u201d  (pp.&nbsp;1231\u20131232).<ref name=\" Phillipson, D. E. 1968\">Phillipson, D.E. (1968). Development of the Roman Law of Debt Security. ''Stanford Law Review, 20''(6), 1230. {{doi|10.2307/1227498}}</ref> Phillipson also describes the leniency of the relationship between debtor and creditor on how it was changed and arranged in the 5th century BC and how [[Roman law]] surrounding it was tweaked within the Twelve Tables that initially drew out the legal boundaries surrounding debt.  Especially discussing the love of creditor's rights, Phillipson states, \u201cIn the fifth century B.C. only movables were pledged under pignus, although any res in which bonitary ownership was held was capable of being pledged. However, by the late Republic, land, and buildings were increasingly pledged in pignus arrangements. This increased usage paralleled the expansion of creditors' rights with respect to the pledged property. The right of possession and seizure (jus possidendi) and the right of foreclosure and sale (just distrained) were probably the most important of the developing creditors' rights. These increased creditors' rights also encouraged and contributed to the expansion of the types of resin which bonitary ownership, and thus pignus arrangements, were possible. For example, the use of pignus expanded to include usufructs, rustic servitudes, rights of way, and even pledges themselves by the second century A.D.\u201d (p.&nbsp;1239).<ref name=\" Phillipson, D. E. 1968\"/>\n\nIn the book, ''The Twelve Tables,'' written by an anonymous source due to its origins being collaborated through a series of translations of tablets and ancient references, P.R. Coleman-Norton arranged and translated many of the significant features of debt that the Twelve Tables enacted into law during the 5th century.  The translation of the legal features surrounding debt and derived from the known sources of the Twelve Tables are stated as such\n\n\u201c1. Of debt acknowledged and for matters judged in court (in iure) thirty days shall be allowed by law [for payment or for satisfaction].\n\n2. After that [elapse of thirty days without payment] hand shall be laid on (manus infection) [the debtor]. He shall be brought into court (in ius).\n\n3. Unless he (the debtor) discharge the debtor unless someone appear in court (in iure) to guarantee payment for him, he (the creditor) shall take [the debtor] with him. He shall bind [him] either with thong or with fetters, of which the weight shall be not less than fifteen pounds or shall be more if he (the creditor) choose.\n\n4. If he (the debtor) chooses, he shall live on his own [means]. If he lives not on his own [means], [the creditor,] who shall hold him in bonds, shall give [him] a pound of bread daily; if he (the creditor) shall so desire, he shall give [him] more.\n\n5. Unless they (the debtors) make a compromise, they (the debtors) shall be held in bonds for sixty days. During those days they shall be brought to [the magistrate] into the comitia (meeting-place) on three successive markets [\u2026]\u201d<ref>Coleman-Norton, P.R. (1960). ''The Twelve Tables''. Princeton: Princeton University, Dept. of Classics.</ref>\n\nThe five mandates of the Twelve Tables encompassing debt created a new understanding within [[Social class in ancient Rome|social classes in ancient Rome]] that insured financial exploitation would be limited within legal business transactions.\n\n=== Women: Tables V, VI & X ===\nThe Twelve Tables have three sections that pertain to women as they concern estates and guardianship, ownership and possession, and religion, which give a basic understanding as to the legal rights of females.\n* '''Table V''' (''Estates and Guardianship''): \u201cFemale heirs should remain under guardianship even when they have attained the age of majority, but exception is made for the Vestal Virgins.\u201d<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The historians of ancient Rome: an anthology of the major writings|last=Mellor|first=Ronald|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0415527163|oclc=819515201}}</ref> \n* '''Table VI''' (''Ownership and Possession''): \u201cWhere a woman, who has not been united to a man in marriage, lives with him for an entire year without an interruption of three nights, she shall pass into his power as his legal wife.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> \n* '''Table X''' (''Religion''): \u201cWomen shall not during a funeral lacerate their faces, or tear their cheeks with their nails; nor shall they utter loud cries bewailing the dead.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\nOne of the aspects highlighted in the Twelve Tables is a woman's legal status and standing in society. Women were considered to be a form of guardianship similar to that of minors,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Hurri|first=Samuli|date=November 2005|title=The Twelve Tables|url=http://www.helsinki.fi/nofo/NoFo1HurriTheTwelveTables.pdf|journal=NoFo|volume=1|pages=13\u201323}}</ref> and sections on ownership and possession give off the impression that women were considered to be akin to a piece of real estate or property due to the use of terms such as \"ownership\" and \"possession\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== The Supplements: Tables XI & XII  ===\n* '''Table XI''' (''Marriage Between Classes''): A person of a certain class shall not partake in marriage with a person of a lower class.\n* '''Table XII''' (''Binding into Law''): Whatever one or more persons have ordered into law, shall be held by the law.\n\n== Influence and significance ==\n[[File:Twelve Tables Engraving.jpg|thumb|Roman civilians examining the Twelve Tables after they were first implemented.]]\nThe Twelve Tables are often cited as the foundation for ancient [[Roman law]]. Although faced with many issues, the Twelve Tables provided a premature understanding of some key concepts such as [[justice]], [[Equality before the law|equality]], and [[punishment]].<ref name=\"jstor.org\">Gary, Forsythe. ''A Critical History of Early Rome: From Prehistory to the First Punic War''. 1st ed., University of California Press, 2005, www.jstor.org/stable/10.1525/j.ctt1ppxrv.</ref> While these ideas were not fully understood, the Twelve Tables play a significant role in the basis of the early American legal system. Political theorists, such as [[James Madison]] have highlighted the importance of the Twelve Tables in crafting the [[United States Bill of Rights]].<ref>Denis, Fustel De Coulanges Numa. ''The Ancient City a Study on the Religion, Laws, and Institutions of Greece and Rome''. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins UP, 2010. Print.</ref> The idea of property was also perpetuated in the Twelve Tables, including the different forms of money, land, and slaves.\n\nAlthough legal reform occurred soon after the implementation of the Twelve Tables, these ancient laws provided [[social protection]] and [[civil rights]] for both the [[Patrician (ancient Rome)|patricians]] and [[plebeians]]. At this time, there was extreme tension between the privileged class and the common people resulting in the need for some form of social order. While the existing laws had major flaws that were in need of reform, the Twelve Tables eased the civil tension and violence between the [[plebeians]] and [[Patrician (ancient Rome)|patricians]].<ref name=\"crystalinks.com\">[http://www.crystalinks.com/romelaw.html \"Law in Ancient Rome, The Twelve Tables\"]. ''www.crystalinks.com''. Retrieved 2017-05-08.</ref>\n\nThe influence of the Twelve Tables is still evident in the modern day. For example, the Twelve Tables are tied into the notion of [[Jus commune|Jus Commune]], which translates as \"common law\", but is commonly referred to as \"civil law\" in English-speaking countries. Some countries including South Africa and San Marino still base their current legal system on aspects of jus commune.<ref name=\"crystalinks.com\"/> In addition, law school students throughout the world are still required to study the Twelve Tables as well as other facets of [[Roman law|Roman Law]] in order to better understand the current legal system in place.<ref>Baker, Keir (2016-04-11). [https://www.theguardian.com/law/2016/apr/11/why-studying-roman-law-is-useful-for-law-students-careers \"Studying Roman law: Juno it's more useful than you'd think\"]. ''The Guardian''. {{ISSN|0261-3077}}. Retrieved 2017-05-08.</ref>\n\n==Sources==\nThe Twelve Tables are no longer extant: although they remained an important source through the [[Roman Republic|Republic]], they gradually became obsolete, eventually being only of historical interest.<ref name=\"Crawford\"/>  The original tablets may have been destroyed when the [[Gaul]]s under [[Brennus (4th century)|Brennus]] burned Rome in 387 BC. [[Cicero]] claimed<ref>Cic. Leg. 2.59</ref> that he learned them by heart as a boy in school, but that no one did so any longer. What we have of them today are brief excerpts and quotations from these laws in other authors, often in clearly updated language. They are written in an archaic, [[Laconic phrase|laconic]] Latin (described as [[Saturnian (poetry)|Saturnian]] verse). As such, though it cannot be determined whether the quoted fragments accurately preserve the original form, what is present gives some insight into the grammar of [[Old Latin|early Latin]]. Some claim that the text was written as such so plebeians could more easily memorize the laws, as literacy was not commonplace during early Rome. Roman Republican scholars wrote commentaries upon the Twelve Tables, such as L. Aelius Stilo,<ref>cf. Funaioli ''GRF'' p57</ref> teacher of both Varro and Cicero.<ref>Cicero, ''Brutus'' 205; Aulus Gellius, ''Attic Nights'' 16.8.2.</ref>\n\nLike most other early codes of law, they were largely [[Roman Litigation|procedural]], combining strict and rigorous penalties with equally strict and rigorous procedural forms. In most of the surviving quotations from these texts, the original table that held them is not given. Scholars have guessed at where surviving fragments belong by comparing them with the few known attributions and records, many of which do not include the original lines, but paraphrases. It cannot be known with any certainty from what survives that the originals ever were organized this way, or even if they ever were organized by subject at all.<ref name=\"Crawford\"/>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Durant\n  |first=W.\n  |authorlink=\n  |title=The Story of Civilization\n  |publisher=Simon and Schuster\n  |year=1942\n  |location=\n  |pages=\n  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T24gAAAAMAAJ\n  |doi=\n  |id=\n  |isbn=}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Livy\n  |last2=De S\u00e9lincourt\n  |first2=A.\n  |last3=Ogilvie\n  |first3=R.M.\n  |last4=Oakley\n  |first4=S.P.\n  |authorlink=\n  |title=The Early History of Rome: Books I\u2013V of The History of Rome from its Foundations\n  |publisher=Penguin Classics\n  |year=2002\n  |location=\n  |pages=\n  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHh7heON3sQC\n  |doi=\n  |id=\n  |isbn=0-14-044809-8}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Goodwin\n  |first=Frederick\n  |authorlink=\n  |title=The XII Tables\n  |publisher=Stevens & Sons\n  |year=1886\n  |location=London\n  |pages=\n  |url=\n  |doi=\n  |id=\n  |isbn=}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Cornell, T.J. 1995. ''The Beginnings of Rome: Italy and Rome from the Bronze Age to the Punic Wars (c. 1000-264 B.C.).'' London: Routledge, Routledge History of the Ancient World. \n* Harries, Jill. 2007. \u201cRoman Law Codes and the Roman Legal Tradition.\u201d In ''Beyond Dogmatics: Law and Society in the Roman World,'' Edited by Cairns, John W. and Du Plessis, Paul J. Edinburgh studies in law; 3, 85-104. Edinburgh: Edinburgh University Pr.\n* Tellegen-Couperus Olga ed. 2011. ''Law and Religion in the Roman Republic.'' Mnemosyne supplements. History and Archaeology of Classical Antiquity, 336.   Leiden; Boston: Brill. \n* Watson, Alan. 1992.  ''The State, Law and Religion: Pagan Rome.'' University of Georgia Press. \n* Westbrook, Raymond. 1988. \"The Nature and Origins of the Twelve Tables.\" ''Zeitschrift der Savigny-Stiftung f\u00fcr Rechtsgeschichte.'' Romanistische Abteilung, CV, 74-121.\n\n==External links==\n{{Library resources box |by=no |onlinebooks=yes |others=yes |about=yes |label=Twelve Tables\n  |viaf= |lccn= |lcheading= |wikititle= }}\n{{Collier's Poster|year=1921|Twelve Tables}}\n*[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Lex_XII_Tabularum.html Entry by George Long in William Smith, ''A Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities'']\n\n{{Ancient Rome topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Constitutions of ancient Rome]]\n[[Category:Roman law]]\n[[Category:Latin inscriptions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Roman statute forming the law}}\n{{Roman government}}\n\nThe '''''Law of the Twelve Tables''''' ({{lang-la|Leges Duodecim Tabularum}} or ''Duodecim Tabulae'') was the legislation that stood at the foundation of [[Roman law]]. The Tables consolidated earlier traditions into an enduring set of laws.<ref>Jolowicz, H.F. ''Historical Introduction to the Study of Roman Law'' (Cambridge, 1952), 108</ref><ref name=\"Crawford\">Crawford, M.H. 'Twelve Tables' in Simon Hornblower, Antony Spawforth, and Esther Eidinow (eds.) ''Oxford Classical Dictionary'' (4th ed.)</ref>\n\nDisplayed in the [[Forum (Roman)|Forum]], \"The Twelve Tables\" stated the rights and duties of the [[Roman citizen]].  Their formulation was the result of considerable agitation by the [[plebeian]] class, who had hitherto been excluded from the higher benefits of the [[Republic]].  The law had previously been unwritten and exclusively interpreted by upper-class priests, the [[pontifices]].  Something of the regard with which later Romans came to view the Twelve Tables is captured in the remark of [[Cicero]] (106\u201343 BC) that the \"Twelve Tables...seems to me, assuredly to surpass the libraries of all the philosophers, both in weight of authority, and in plenitude of utility\".  Cicero scarcely exaggerated; the Twelve Tables formed the basis of Roman law for a thousand years.<ref>Book: \"[[The Age of Classical Civilization]]\"; Chapter \"The Twelve Tables c. 450 BC\"; p. 27</ref>\n\nThe Twelve Tables are sufficiently comprehensive that their substance has been described as a 'code',<ref>Mommsen, T. ''The History of Rome'' trans. W.P. Dickson (London,\n1864) 290</ref> although modern scholars consider this characterization exaggerated.<ref name=\"Crawford\"/> The Tables were a sequence of definitions of various private rights and procedures. They generally took for granted such things as the institutions of the family and various rituals for formal transactions. The provisions were often highly specific and diverse.<ref>Steinberg, S. 'The Twelve Tables and Their Origins: An Eighteenth-Century Debate' ''Journal of the History of Ideas'' Vol. 43, No. 3 (1982) 379\u2013396, 381</ref>\n\n==Drafting and development==\nThe Twelve Tables of Roman society were said by the Romans to have come about as a result of the long social struggle between patricians and plebeians. After the expulsion of the last king of Rome, [[Lucius Tarquinius Superbus|Tarquinius Superbus]], the [[Roman Republic|Republic]] was governed by a hierarchy of [[Roman Magistrate|magistrates]]. Initially, only [[patrician (ancient Rome)|patricians]] were eligible to become magistrates and this, among other plebeian complaints, was a source of discontent for [[plebeians]]. In the context of this unequal status, plebeians would take action to secure concessions for themselves using the threat of secession. They would threaten to leave the city with the consequence that it would grind to a halt, as the plebeians were Rome's labor force. Tradition held that one of the most important concessions won in this class struggle was the establishment of the ''Twelve Tables'', establishing basic procedural rights for all Roman citizens in relation to each other.<ref name=\"du Plessis 5-6; 29-30\">{{cite book|last=du Plessis|first=Paul|title=Borkowski's Textbook on Roman Law|year=2010|publisher=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-957488-9|pages=5\u20136, 29\u201330|edition=4th}}</ref> The drafting of the Twelve Tables may have been fomented by a desire for self-regulation by the patricians, or for other reasons.<ref name=\"Crawford\"/>\n\nAround 450 BC, the first ''[[decemviri]]'' (decemvirate, board of \"Ten Men\") were appointed to draw up the first ten tables. According to [[Titus Livius|Livy]], they sent an embassy to [[Greece]] to study the legislative system of [[Athens]], known as the [[Solonian Constitution]], but also to find out about the legislation of other [[Greeks|Greek]] cities.<ref>Livy, 2002, p. 23</ref><ref>Durant, 1942, p. 23</ref> Some scholars deny that the Romans imitated the Greeks in this respect<ref>Steinberg, S. 'The Twelve Tables and Their Origins: An Eighteenth-Century Debate' ''Journal of the History of Ideas'' Vol. 43, No. 3 (1982) 379\u2013396</ref> or suggest that they visited only the Greek cities of [[Magna Graecia|Southern Italy]], and did not travel all the way to Greece.<ref name=\"Grant 75\">{{cite book|last=Grant|first=Michael|title=History of Rome|year=1978|publisher=Prentice Hall|isbn=0-02-345610-8|pages=75|edition=1st}}</ref> In 450 BC, the second ''decemviri'' started to work on the last two tables.\n\nThe first decemvirate completed the first ten codes in 450 BC. Here is how [[Livy]] describes their creation:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"...every citizen should quietly consider each point, then talk it over with his friends, and, finally, bring forward for public discussion any additions or subtractions which seemed desirable.\" (cf. Liv. [[s:From the Founding of the City/Book 3#34|III.34]])\n</blockquote>\n\nIn 449 BC, the second decemvirate completed the last two codes, and after a ''[[secessio plebis]]'' to force the Senate to consider them, the Law of the Twelve Tables was formally promulgated.<ref>McCarty,  Nick \"Rome The Greatest Empire of the Ancient World\", The Rosen Publishing Group, 2008</ref>  According to Livy (AUC [[s:From the Founding of the City/Book 3#57|3.57.10]]) the Twelve Tables were inscribed on [[bronze]] (Pomponius (Dig. 1 tit. 2 s2 \u00a74) alone says on ivory), and posted publicly, so all Romans could read and know them.\n\nSome of the provisions are procedural to ensure fairness among all Romans in the courts, while other established legal terms dictating the legality of capital crimes, intentional homicide, treason, perjury, judicial corruption, and writing slanderous poems.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Romans valued keeping peace in the city and the Twelve Tables were a mechanism of establishing and continuing peace and equality.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Laws of the Twelve Tables ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Table 1\n|Procedure: for courts and trials\n|-\n|Table 2\n|Trials continued & Theft\n|-\n|Table 3\n|Debt\n|-\n|Table 4\n|Rights of fathers (''pater familias'') over the family\n|-\n|Table 5\n|Legal guardianship and inheritance laws\n|-\n|Table 6\n|Acquisition and possession\n|-\n|Table 7\n|Land rights & crimes\n|-\n|Table 8\n|Torts and delicts (Laws of injury)\n|-\n|Table 9\n|Public law\n|-\n|Table 10\n|Sacred law\n|-\n|Table 11\n|Supplement I\n|-\n|Table 12\n|Supplement II\n|}\n\n=== Table III: Debt ===\nThe [[laws]] the Twelve Tables covered were a way to publicly display rights that each citizen had in the public and private sphere.  These Twelve Tables displayed what was previously understood in Roman society as the unwritten laws.  The public display of the copper tablets allowed for a more balanced society between the Roman [[Patrician (ancient Rome)|patricians]] who were educated and understood the laws of legal transactions, and the Roman [[Plebeian (ancient Rome)|plebians]] who had little education or experience in understanding law.  By revealing the unwritten rules of society to the public, the Twelve Tables provided a means of safeguard for Plebeians allowing them the opportunity to avoid financial exploitation and added balance to the [[Roman economy]]\n\nFeatured within the Twelve Tables are five rules about how to handle debtors and creditors. These rules show how the ancient Romans maintained peace with financial policy.  In his article ''Development of the Roman Law of Debt Security,'' Donald E. Phillipson states the Twelve Tables were, \u201cA set of statutes known as the Twelve Tables that was passed by an early assembly served as the foundation of the Roman private law.  The Twelve Tables were enacted in the mid-fifth century B.C. as the result of a conflict among social classes in ancient Rome.\u201d  (pp. 1231\u20131232).<ref name=\" Phillipson, D. E. 1968\">Phillipson, D.E. (1968). Development of the Roman Law of Debt Security. ''Stanford Law Review, 20''(6), 1230. {{doi|10.2307/1227498}}</ref> Phillipson also describes the leniency of the relationship between debtor and creditor on how it was changed and arranged in the 5th century BC and how [[Roman law]] surrounding it was tweaked within the Twelve Tables that initially drew out the legal boundaries surrounding debt.  Especially discussing the love of creditor's rights, Phillipson states, \u201cIn the fifth century B.C. only movables were pledged under pignus, although any res in which bonitary ownership was held was capable of being pledged. However, by the late Republic, land, and buildings were increasingly pledged in pignus arrangements. This increased usage paralleled the expansion of creditors' rights with respect to the pledged property. The right of possession and seizure (jus possidendi) and the right of foreclosure and sale (just distrained) were probably the most important of the developing creditors' rights. These increased creditors' rights also encouraged and contributed to the expansion of the types of resin which bonitary ownership, and thus pignus arrangements, were possible. For example, the use of pignus expanded to include usufructs, rustic servitudes, rights of way, and even pledges themselves by the second century A.D.\u201d (p. 1239).<ref name=\" Phillipson, D. E. 1968\"/>\n\nIn the book, ''The Twelve Tables,'' written by an anonymous source due to its origins being collaborated through a series of translations of tablets and ancient references, P.R. Coleman-Norton arranged and translated many of the significant features of debt that the Twelve Tables enacted into law during the 5th century.  The translation of the legal features surrounding debt and derived from the known sources of the Twelve Tables are stated as such\n\n\u201c1. Of debt acknowledged and for matters judged in court (in iure) thirty days shall be allowed by law [for payment or for satisfaction].\n\n2. After that [elapse of thirty days without payment] hand shall be laid on (manus infection) [the debtor]. He shall be brought into court (in ius).\n\n3. Unless he (the debtor) discharge the debtor unless someone appear in court (in iure) to guarantee payment for him, he (the creditor) shall take [the debtor] with him. He shall bind [him] either with thong or with fetters, of which the weight shall be not less than fifteen pounds or shall be more if he (the creditor) choose.\n\n4. If he (the debtor) chooses, he shall live on his own [means]. If he lives not on his own [means], [the creditor,] who shall hold him in bonds, shall give [him] a pound of bread daily; if he (the creditor) shall so desire, he shall give [him] more.\n\n5. Unless they (the debtors) make a compromise, they (the debtors) shall be held in bonds for sixty days. During those days they shall be brought to [the magistrate] into the comitia (meeting-place) on three successive markets [\u2026]\u201d<ref>Coleman-Norton, P.R. (1960). ''The Twelve Tables''. Princeton: Princeton University, Dept. of Classics.</ref>\n\nThe five mandates of the Twelve Tables encompassing debt created a new understanding within [[Social class in ancient Rome|social classes in ancient Rome]] that insured financial exploitation would be limited within legal business transactions.\n\n=== Women: Tables V, VI & X ===\nThe Twelve Tables have three sections that pertain to women as they concern estates and guardianship, ownership and possession, and religion, which give a basic understanding as to the legal rights of females.\n* '''Table V''' (''Estates and Guardianship''): \u201cFemale heirs should remain under guardianship even when they have attained the age of majority, but exception is made for the Vestal Virgins.\u201d<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The historians of ancient Rome: an anthology of the major writings|last=Mellor|first=Ronald|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0415527163|oclc=819515201}}</ref> \n* '''Table VI''' (''Ownership and Possession''): \u201cWhere a woman, who has not been united to a man in marriage, lives with him for an entire year without an interruption of three nights, she shall pass into his power as his legal wife.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> \n* '''Table X''' (''Religion''): \u201cWomen shall not during a funeral lacerate their faces, or tear their cheeks with their nails; nor shall they utter loud cries bewailing the dead.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\nOne of the aspects highlighted in the Twelve Tables is a woman's legal status and standing in society. Women were considered to be a form of guardianship similar to that of minors,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Hurri|first=Samuli|date=November 2005|title=The Twelve Tables|url=http://www.helsinki.fi/nofo/NoFo1HurriTheTwelveTables.pdf|journal=NoFo|volume=1|pages=13\u201323}}</ref> and sections on ownership and possession give off the impression that women were considered to be akin to a piece of real estate or property due to the use of terms such as \"ownership\" and \"possession\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== The Supplements: Tables XI & XII  ===\n* '''Table XI''' (''Marriage Between Classes''): A person of a certain class shall not partake in marriage with a person of a lower class.\n\n* '''Table XII''' (''Binding into Law''): Whatever one or more persons have ordered into law, shall be held by the law.\n\n== Influence and significance ==\n[[File:Twelve Tables Engraving.jpg|thumb|Roman civilians examining the Twelve Tables after they were first implemented.]]\nThe Twelve Tables are often cited as the foundation for ancient [[Roman law]]. Although faced with many issues, the Twelve Tables provided a premature understanding of some key concepts such as [[justice]], [[Equality before the law|equality]], and [[punishment]].<ref name=\"jstor.org\">Gary, Forsythe. ''A Critical History of Early Rome: From Prehistory to the First Punic War''. 1st ed., University of California Press, 2005, www.jstor.org/stable/10.1525/j.ctt1ppxrv.</ref> While these ideas were not fully understood, the Twelve Tables play a significant role in the basis of the early American legal system. Political theorists, such as [[James Madison]] have highlighted the importance of the Twelve Tables in crafting the [[United States Bill of Rights]].<ref>Denis, Fustel De Coulanges Numa. ''The Ancient City a Study on the Religion, Laws, and Institutions of Greece and Rome''. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins UP, 2010. Print.</ref> The idea of property was also perpetuated in the Twelve Tables, including the different forms of money, land, and slaves.\n\nAlthough legal reform occurred soon after the implementation of the Twelve Tables, these ancient laws provided [[social protection]] and [[civil rights]] for both the [[Patrician (ancient Rome)|patricians]] and [[plebeians]]. At this time, there was extreme tension between the privileged class and the common people resulting in the need for some form of social order. While the existing laws had major flaws that were in need of reform, the Twelve Tables eased the civil tension and violence between the [[plebeians]] and [[Patrician (ancient Rome)|patricians]].<ref name=\"crystalinks.com\">[http://www.crystalinks.com/romelaw.html \"Law in Ancient Rome, The Twelve Tables\"]. ''www.crystalinks.com''. Retrieved 2017-05-08.</ref>\n\nThe influence of the Twelve Tables is still evident in the modern day. For example, the Twelve Tables are tied into the notion of [[Jus commune|Jus Commune]], which translates as \"common law\", but is commonly referred to as \"civil law\" in English-speaking countries. Some countries including South Africa and San Marino still base their current legal system on aspects of jus commune.<ref name=\"crystalinks.com\"/> In addition, law school students throughout the world are still required to study the Twelve Tables as well as other facets of [[Roman law|Roman Law]] in order to better understand the current legal system in place.<ref>Baker, Keir (2016-04-11). [https://www.theguardian.com/law/2016/apr/11/why-studying-roman-law-is-useful-for-law-students-careers \"Studying Roman law: Juno it's more useful than you'd think\"]. ''The Guardian''. {{ISSN|0261-3077}}. Retrieved 2017-05-08.</ref>\n\n==Sources==\nThe Twelve Tables are no longer extant: although they remained an important source through the [[Roman Republic|Republic]], they gradually became obsolete, eventually being only of historical interest.<ref name=\"Crawford\"/>  The original tablets may have been destroyed when the [[Gaul]]s under [[Brennus (4th century)|Brennus]] burned Rome in 387 BC. [[Cicero]] claimed<ref>Cic. Leg. 2.59</ref> that he learned them by heart as a boy in school, but that no one did so any longer. What we have of them today are brief excerpts and quotations from these laws in other authors, often in clearly updated language. They are written in an archaic, [[Laconic phrase|laconic]] Latin (described as [[Saturnian (poetry)|Saturnian]] verse). As such, though it cannot be determined whether the quoted fragments accurately preserve the original form, what is present gives some insight into the grammar of [[Old Latin|early Latin]]. Some claim that the text was written as such so plebeians could more easily memorize the laws, as literacy was not commonplace during early Rome. Roman Republican scholars wrote commentaries upon the Twelve Tables, such as L. Aelius Stilo,<ref>cf. Funaioli ''GRF'' p57</ref> teacher of both Varro and Cicero.<ref>Cicero, ''Brutus'' 205; Aulus Gellius, ''Attic Nights'' 16.8.2.</ref>\n\nLike most other early codes of law, they were largely [[Roman Litigation|procedural]], combining strict and rigorous penalties with equally strict and rigorous procedural forms. In most of the surviving quotations from these texts, the original table that held them is not given. Scholars have guessed at where surviving fragments belong by comparing them with the few known attributions and records, many of which do not include the original lines, but paraphrases. It cannot be known with any certainty from what survives that the originals ever were organized this way, or even if they ever were organized by subject at all.<ref name=\"Crawford\"/>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Durant\n  |first=W.\n  |authorlink=\n  |title=The Story of Civilization\n  |publisher=Simon and Schuster\n  |year=1942\n  |location=\n  |pages=\n  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T24gAAAAMAAJ\n  |doi=\n  |id=\n  |isbn=}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Livy\n  |last2=De S\u00e9lincourt\n  |first2=A.\n  |last3=Ogilvie\n  |first3=R.M.\n  |last4=Oakley\n  |first4=S.P.\n  |authorlink=\n  |title=The Early History of Rome: Books I\u2013V of The History of Rome from its Foundations\n  |publisher=Penguin Classics\n  |year=2002\n  |location=\n  |pages=\n  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHh7heON3sQC\n  |doi=\n  |id=\n  |isbn=0-14-044809-8}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Goodwin\n  |first=Frederick\n  |authorlink=\n  |title=The XII Tables\n  |publisher=Stevens & Sons\n  |year=1886\n  |location=London\n  |pages=\n  |url=\n  |doi=\n  |id=\n  |isbn=}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Cornell, T.J. 1995. ''The Beginnings of Rome: Italy and Rome from the Bronze 